1. e4 c6 { The Caro Kann was "a solid workhorse" in the world champion's opening repertoire to get a quiet game in his matches against Smyslov. } 2. Nc3 d5 3. Nf3 { Apparently both Botvinnik and Tal believed at the time of the WCC that the two knight's Caro was a better winning attempt for white than the main line. } (3. d4 { The main line. } 3... dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 { Several games between Smyslov and Botvinnik were played in this variation. }) 3... Bg4 4. h3 Bxf3 (4... Bh5?! 5. exd5! cxd5 6. Bb5+ (6. g4!? Bg6 7. h4! $14 { If there is a refutation to black's move order, it might just be this variation. }) 6... Nc6 7. g4 Bg6 8. Ne5 Rc8 9. d4 e6 10. Qe2! Bb4?! (10... Bd6! $14 { The better try for black. } { Venkatesh, Marani Rajendran - Ding, Liren, 0-1, Asian Continental op, 2012, https://lichess.org/XAqc9XEH }) 11. h4! Qb6 12. O-O! $16 { A game played at the 1960 Latvian championship that Tal references. Indeed, this does appear to refute black's suboptimal play. }) 5. gxf3!? $146 { Tal's novelty was universally condemned at the time. But in the post-engine era, this very well might be a reasonable try seen at the top level. Not only is it a 0.0 variation, but the play is fundamentally different from the main lines, so you're getting both a practical advantage and playable position. } 5... e6 { Botvinnik chooses a solid continuation, keeping the light squares defended and the center reasonably closed, during the game after 16 minutes. } (5... e5?! { A training game played before the match with his second, Alexander Koblents. } 6. f4! dxe4 (6... exf4 7. exd5 cxd5 8. d4 $10 { Transposing to a favorable version of the King's gambit. }) 7. fxe5 Qd4 8. Qe2 Qxe5 9. d4! Qxd4 10. Nxe4 Be7 11. Bf4 Qxb2? (11... Nd7! { The only playable way to continue. } 12. Bg2 O-O-O 13. O-O $14 { With play similar to the Qd6 Scandi when black gets greedy and takes on d4. }) 12. Nd6+!! { Not played in the practice game. Would have finished him off directly. } (12. Rd1? { The game continuation. } 12... Nf6 13. Nd6+ Kf8 $10 { and we arrive at a position that was featured in the advanced section of the Woodpecker Method. Try your hand at it before checking the solution! https://lichess.org/study/H4guLgm0/7hoZiEqk }) 12... Kf8 13. Be5! Qb4+ 14. c3! Qc5 15. Nxb7! { Now this move works! } 15... Qb6 16. Bxg7+!! Kxg7!? (16... Ke8!? 17. Nd6+ $18) 17. Qg4+ Kf8 18. Qc8+ Kg7!? (18... Bd8!? 19. Nxd8 $18) 19. Rg1+ $18) (5... d4!? { This move scores reasonably well in the masters database: } 6. Ne2 c5 7. f4 e6 $10) 6. d4 Nd7!? (6... Nf6!? 7. e5?! (7. Qd3 $10) 7... Nfd7 $15 { Tal thought this would only be beneficial to white. But with such a locked position, the value of time decreases. And there's no way to quickly get in f4-f5. So black is totally fine here. }) 7. Bf4?! { Tal spent 8 minutes over the board to play a poor move. } (7. Be3! { Tal's preparation. With Qd2 and O-O-O coming next, white has some play. } 7... Bb4 8. Qd2 Ngf6 9. Bd3 $10) 7... Bb4 8. h4 { "And this is a simple blunder based on a miscalcalculation." even though the engine finds this move totally fine. } (8. a3?! Ba5?! (8... Bxc3+ 9. bxc3 Ngf6 $15 { White has a beefy center, but in typical Winawer style, we would rather play Bc1->a3 here. Black has just enough play as long as they don't blast open the center. }) 9. b4?! Bc7 { Winning a tempo. } 10. Be3 Ne7 $15) 8... Ngf6 (8... Ne7?! 9. h5 $10 { The point of h4. Black's knight is struggling to find a square. }) 9. e5?! { "After this move, white is positionally lost, since all of his hopes for an open game have disappeared and along with them any compensation for the numerous weaknesses in his camp."
Tal played this move after 23 minutes of analyzing unforced variations where he found better moves for black than for white. He should have searched broad, not deep! } (9. Qd3!? { "clumsy." } 9... Qa5 10. Bd2 $10 { It's tough to retreat like this and admit your last moves were bad. }) (9. a3?! { Tal's original idea was to "begin gambit play" } 9... Bxc3+ 10. bxc3 dxe4 11. fxe4 Nxe4 { This is the first position Tal should have really looked broad on rather than assume Qf3 had to be correct. } 12. Qf3!? Qa5!? { His main fear is probably not even black's best move. } (12... f5! $15 { The inhuman move refutes white's play. The knight cannot be dislodged. }) 13. Rh3!? (13. Rb1! { The c pawn is still taboo because of: } 13... Nxc3? (13... Qxc3+? 14. Qxc3 Nxc3 15. Rxb7 $16 { The position has blown open for the bishops. }) (13... Ndf6!? 14. Rxb7 $15 { Some compensation in the form of the two bishops. }) 14. Bd2! $16) 13... Ndf6 14. h5? { Also completely not forced. } 14... O-O-O 15. h6 gxh6 16. Be5 Ng5 17. Qxf6 Nxh3 18. Kd2 Ng5 19. Bd3 { "I examined this position thinking that white has a fine initiative for being down the exchange, but suddenly I felt a shiver go down my spine when I saw: " } 19... Qxe5!! $19 { Tal should have gone broad, not deep though. None of this was forced. }) 9... Nh5 10. Bg5 (10. Bd2!? Qb6 $15 { transposes to the game. }) 10... Qa5 (10... f6!? 11. f4 g6 12. Bh6 $15 { "some vague hope of creating play against the e pawn." You can already tell how desperate he sounds in his annotations. White's doing fine here. }) 11. Bd2 { A finesse to provoke the queen to be opposite the bishop. } 11... Qb6 12. a3 Be7 (12... Bxc3?! 13. bxc3! $10 { With typical Winawer play, white is doing totally fine here. }) 13. Be3?! (13. f4!? { An interesting approach to blast open the kingside even at the cost of the center. } 13... g6 14. Be2 Ng7!? (14... Qxd4!? 15. Bxh5 gxh5 16. Qxh5 $10) 15. h5! Nxh5 16. Bxh5 gxh5 17. Qxh5 $10) 13... g6! (13... Qxb2?? 14. Na4 $18) 14. Na4 (14. f4?! Ng7 15. Be2 h5! $15 { Now white is not in time to force through h5. Black retains the grip. }) 14... Qd8 { Concentrating on the original plan: the h4 pawn. But this move undevelops the queen and so gives white more opportunities to blow it all open. } (14... Qa5+?! 15. Qd2!? (15. c3!? b5 16. Nc5 Bxc5 17. b4! $10) 15... Qxa4?! (15... Qxd2+!? 16. Kxd2 $15) 16. b3! Bb4! 17. Qxb4 Qxb4+ 18. axb4 $14 { The type of sharp play Tal was looking for. }) 15. Qd2?! { Tal misses his chance to truly sharpen up the position. } (15. f4! Bxh4!? (15... Ng7!? 16. h5! Nxh5 17. Rxh5 gxh5 18. Qxh5 $10 { Again, this exchange sac hits just in time. }) 16. Qg4! Be7 17. Rxh5! gxh5 18. Qxh5 $10 { Black is so underdeveloped that they can't get the king castled away to the queenside fast enough. White is blowing open the center next with f5. }) 15... Ng7 (15... Bxh4!? { "Interesting variations can arise." But that favors white who is statically worse and needs to look for dynamic complications. } 16. Bh6 $13 { [%cal Gf1h3,Gh3g4] } (16. Rxh4?! { Tal also considered this enterprising exchange sac. } 16... Qxh4 17. Bg5 Qh2 18. Qb4 f6 19. Qxb7 O-O!? (19... Rb8?! 20. Qxc6 fxg5 21. Qxe6+ (21. Nc5?! O-O 22. Nxd7 $15 { Tal's line is less convincing. This leads to a "not unfavorable game for white." }) 21... Kd8 22. Nc5 Nhf6! $10 { Petrosian's analysis after the game is more correct than Tal's. }) 20. Bh6 Rfd8 21. Qxc6 { Tal felt this was enough compensation for the exchange... but it's not after: } 21... Nf8! 22. Bxf8 Rxf8 23. Qxe6+ Kh8 $17 { White has just been playing with the pretty pieces. Black's king is finally safe and white can't castle queenside without dropping f2 or allowing Nf4. })) 16. Bg5 (16. Bd3?! h5! $15 { Mostly plays into black's hands. }) 16... h6! (16... Nf5?! 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 18. h5! $10 { "white's position would have improved greatly" as the h pawn has been offloaded. }) (16... f6! $15 { The correct way to punish Tal. But Botvinnik consistently avoids these tactical melees. }) 17. Bxh6?! { Tal keeps his bishop pair, but now black can win the h pawn and once again retains some initiative. } (17. Bxe7!? Qxe7 { As long as the queens remain on the board, white has no true issues in the position. Black should be torn between getting his king to safety and attacking white's center. } 18. Bd3! (18. Qb4? b6 $17) 18... Nf5?! (18... O-O-O!? 19. b4 Kb8 20. Nc5 $10 { This remains totally playable for white. }) (18... Kf8!? 19. O-O-O $10) 19. Bxf5 gxf5 20. b4! { Once c5 is ruled out, white can utilize the f4 square for the knight! } 20... O-O-O 21. Nb2 Kb8 22. Nd3 Ka8 $10 { [%cal Gd3f4] }) 17... Nf5! 18. Bf4 Rxh4 19. Rxh4 Nxh4 20. O-O-O! { The f pawn cannot be defended. } (20. Qe3? Qa5+ 21. Nc3 c5 $17) (20. Be2? Ng2+! 21. Kf1 Nxf4 { Depriving white of the two bishops. } 22. Qxf4 Qa5 $17) 20... b5! 21. Nc5!? { "One more desperate attempt to get back the initiative at the cost of a pawn." } (21. Nc3!? a5 $15 { "Passive tactics would be absolutely disastrous for white." The engine is not impressed yet with black's attack. } { [%cal Gb5b4] } 22. Kb1!? b4 23. Na4! bxa3 24. b3 { and asks black to show white the money. }) 21... Nxc5 22. dxc5 Bxc5 23. Be2 (23. Bg5?? Nxf3 $19) 23... Be7!? { Prevents Bg5, but it's another slow move. } (23... Nf5!? { Also takes the sting out of Bg5. } 24. Rh1!? (24. Bg5!? Qc7 25. f4!? (25. Rh1? Qxe5 $17) 25... Kd7 26. Rh1 Kc8 27. Rh7 Kb7 $17 { Another example where black doesn't dally and immediately fixes the king while coordinating the remaining pieces. }) 24... Kd7 25. Rh7 Qg8 $17 { Much cleaner coordination to accomplish the same thing done in the game. }) 24. Kb1! { Prevents black from getting the king to the queenside directly. } 24... Qc7!? (24... Kd7!? 25. c4!? bxc4 26. Bxc4 $17 { and yet this remains lost for white anyway. }) 25. Rh1 O-O-O 26. Bg3 Nf5 27. Rh7 { "Probably white's first active move in this game." } 27... Rf8?! { "Safe but passive continuation." } (27... Nxg3?! 28. fxg3 Qxe5 29. Rxf7 { For some reason, Tal doesn't even analyze this obvious move, which is best. } (29. f4?! Qf6 30. Qa5 Bc5! $17 { [%cal Gd8d7] }) 29... Bf6 30. c3 $10) (27... Rd7! 28. Rxf7!? Bb4! 29. Rxd7 Bxd2 30. Rxc7+ Kxc7 $17 { With such a locked position, both of white's bishops are dead. Still, converting this to a win will require good technique. }) 28. Bf4 Qd8?! (28... Bc5! { "Necessary." } 29. Bd3 $15 { The f pawn is defended by the queen, so Bxf5 and Bh6 don't win the f pawn. }) 29. Bd3 Rh8?! { Black has not embraced the fact that white's attempts to dynamically blow open the position would have backfired while black was positionally better.
Now, black gives up both the advantage and also spent 7 minutes to do so. He now only has 11 minutes to play 11 moves. For the slow Botvinnik, that is severe time pressure. } (29... c5! $15 { A cleaner way forward. White gets nowhere by trying to win either pawn. } 30. Bxb5?! (30. Bxf5?! gxf5 31. Bh6 Rg8 32. Rxf7 Rg1+ 33. Ka2 d4 $17 { And finally black has activated all of his pieces. }) (30. c3!? $15 { It is in no way easy to play this for either side. And Botvinnik would never play such a risky move while approaching time pressure. }) 30... g5! $17) (29... g5?! 30. Bh2? (30. Bg3!? { The better try. } 30... Rh8 31. Rxf7 $15) 30... Rh8 31. Bxf5 exf5 32. Qd3! Rxh7? (32... f4! $19 { Pawns aren't people. This is another classic example in the mold of Winter - Capablanca, 1912. White's bishop is entombed! }) 33. Qxf5+ Qd7 34. Qxh7 Qe6 35. f4! $10 { Tal's idea to get counterplay. Once again, he's too fanciful with the variations and missing tactical resources for both players earlier in the lines. }) 30. Rxh8 { Played after 21 minutes as Tal tried to calculate a full rook sacrifice. With both players now desperately low on time, this should be marked as clearly unpractical. Save the time! } (30. Rxf7?! Qe8 31. Qa5? (31. Rf6!? Bxf6 32. exf6 e5! $15 { "Insufficient compensation for the exchange" }) 31... Qxf7 32. Qxa7 { [%cal Ga3a4] } 32... Rh7! 33. a4 Bd8! 34. Qa8+ Kd7 35. axb5 Ke8! $19 { Tal refuted his own attempt at a perpetual. }) 30... Qxh8 31. Qa5! Qh1+ (31... Qd8?! 32. Qxa7 $14) (31... Kb7?! 32. Bxb5! { The only way forward. } 32... cxb5 33. Qxb5+ Kc7!? (33... Ka8!? 34. Qc6+ Kb8 35. Qb5+ $10) 34. Bd2! $10 { With a perpetual at least. }) (31... Kb8!? { The move Tal was most worried about during the game. } 32. Bxb5?? (32. Bxf5! { Tal thought this move lost but in fact it's good enough for a perpetual. } 32... Qh1+! (32... gxf5?? 33. Be3! $16 { The point. }) 33. Ka2 Qxf3 34. Be3?? (34. Qa6! { An improvement! } 34... Qxf4!? (34... gxf5!? 35. Qxc6! Qxf4 36. Qe8+ Kc7 37. Qxe7+ $10) 35. Bd3 Qxe5 36. Qxc6 Qc7 37. Qxb5+ Kc8 38. Qe8+ Bd8 39. Ba6+ Kb8 $10) 34... d4! 35. Bxd4 Qd5+! $19 { Tal found this "refutation" during the game. }) (32. a4!? { Tal's supposed improvement allows black to actually just bail with: } 32... Qd8! 33. Qa6 Qc8! 34. Qxc8+ Kxc8 35. axb5 Nd4 $15 { Not at all easy to see or evaluate. }) 32... Bd8! $19) 32. Ka2 Qxf3 33. Qa6+! Kb8 34. Qxc6! Qxf4 35. Bxb5!? { The threat of Ba6 forces black's hand: } (35. Qxb5+!? Kc7 36. Qa5+ Kb8 37. Qb5+ $10) 35... Qxe5 36. Qe8+ Kb7?! { Almost throws the game away, but black is still fine here. } (36... Kc7!? $10 { "More prudent" because now white can force a perpetual, but white doesn't have any winning chances. }) 37. Qc6+!? (37. Ba6+! { "Practically speaking this might have good chances, but white's position had been so bad throughout the game that he decided not to tempt face and therefore forced the draw." } 37... Kxa6 { Forced. } (37... Kc7?? 38. Qc8+ Kb6 39. Qb7+ Kc5 40. Qb4+ Kc6 41. Qb5+ Kc7 42. Qb7+ Kd6 43. Qb8+! Kc6 44. Qxe5 $18) 38. Qc6+ Ka5 39. c3! { The threat of b4# is so dire that black has only one move to prevent it: } 39... Qe2! 40. Qc7+ Ka6 41. Qc6+ $10 { Perpetual. }) 37... Kb8 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { With a perpetual on the board, and neither player having any time on their clock, both players agreed to a draw rather than play out the repetition. } 1/2-1/2


