[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.04.07"]
[Round "11"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Result "1-0"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A05"]
[Opening "King's Indian Attack: Symmetrical Defense"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 11: Tal - Botvinnik, Symmetric Grunfeld"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/n1FgwAhE"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Tal has a beautiful explanation about past matches between Capablanca, Alekhine, Lasker, etc being decided during the middle of the match. Psychologically speaking, a game or set of games in the middle has historically given the winner of the match a confidence to close out the match. Indeed, this trend has continued to today, with Carlsen's 2021 match against Nepomniatchi being decided by the monumental effort in game 6.

With that being said, Tal's trainer decided that it would be better to switch away from 1. e4 for the time being because his positions in the Caro Kann have not led to anything. }
1. Nf3!? { Tal avoids his favorite 1. e4. } 1... Nf6 2. g3 g6!? { Botvinnik has never played the Benoni or KID, so presumably this is an offer to transpose to the Grunfeld. } 3. Bg2 Bg7 4. O-O O-O 5. c4 c6 6. b3!? { Avoiding a direct transposition to the symmetric Grunfeld. } (6. d4!? d5 { The main line symmetric Grunfeld. Tal believed the only way to play was cxd5 but modern times have shown that white has several options available. } 7. cxd5!? (7. Qb3!?) 7... cxd5 8. Ne5! $10 { has been tested at the top level as a way to play for an advantage. }) 6... Ne4!? { Botvinnik plays this move after 15 minutes, now having already spent 23 minutes just to play the opening. } (6... d5!? 7. Bb2 $10 { "There arises a complicated position with an unclear center formation." This is a very modern idea, in actual fact. Tal is just trying to get a game, where theoretical considerations are neither here nor there. }) 7. d4 d5 8. Bb2 Be6?! { Botvinnik has now played two odd moves. In response, Tal decides to sacrifice the c pawn after only 10 minutes. } (8... a5!? $10 { "probably stronger." Agreed - this is very thematic in these Catalan-type positions. }) (8... Nd7!? 9. Nfd2 $10 { Driving the knight out of e4 was Tal's idea. }) 9. Nbd2! Nxd2 (9... f5!? 10. Nxe4 fxe4 11. Ng5 Bf5 12. f3 { Tal thought that losing another tempo with the bishop would make this worth it for white The engine is not impressed after: } 12... exf3 13. exf3?! (13. Rxf3!? Na6 $10 { White has lost control over e4 and therefore doesn't have the "significant positional advantage" Tal thought existed in the position. }) 13... h6! 14. Nh3 dxc4! $15) 10. Qxd2! { Absolutely correct. Black's entire setup is now questioned. Do you really want to win the c pawn? } (10. Nxd2?! c5! $10 { Equalizing in the center and putting the two bishops on e6 and g7 to good use. }) 10... Na6?! { Black hurries to finish development, now having spent 51 minutes. Tal's slight space advantage and more harmonious pieces give him a slight edge. } (10... dxc4!? { The obvious capture of the pawn in combination to the other awkward moves black has already made, really does push it over the edge. } 11. Ng5! Qd6!? (11... Bd5?! 12. e4 h6 13. exd5 hxg5 14. bxc4 $16) (11... Bh6?! 12. h4 $14) (11... cxb3?! 12. Nxe6 fxe6 13. axb3! $16 (13. Qe3!? $16 { Vachier Lagrave, M. - Aronian, L., 1-0, 2nd Sinquefield Cup 2014, https://lichess.org/gT1PflLR })) 12. Nxe6 Qxe6 13. bxc4 Qxc4 { White has the bishop pair, and black has moved their queen all over the board, so the thematic continuation: } 14. d5! (14. Rfc1?! Qa6 $10 { Jansa, Vlastimil - Biolek, Richard, 1-0, CZE-chT 0405, 2005, https://lichess.org/SMwwCCqp }) 14... Bxb2 15. Qxb2 $14 { is best. }) (10... h6!? { Ng5 is prevented, and so black can hope to develop naturally next. } 11. Ne5!? Nd7 12. Nd3 $14 { Yet again, the c pawn should not be captured when Nf4, further harassing the bishop, is available. }) (10... c5? { One useful point of the queen being on d2 is to prevent the thematic c5 pawn break. } 11. dxc5 Bxb2 12. Qxb2 dxc4 13. Nd4 $16) (10... Nd7? { The more normal post fails to } 11. Ng5! $16) 11. Rac1 Qd6 12. Ne5 { A thematic hop in the Catalan. } 12... Rfd8 (12... f6?! 13. Nd3 $16 { and black's g7 bishop is buried. }) 13. Rfd1!? (13. f4!? { Playable. With g4 and f5 coming, there can be a lot of heat brought against black's kingside. }) 13... Rac8 14. Qa5!? { Tal gives this move an exclamation mark. However, just because a move is unnatural and can't be refuted doesn't mean it's objectively strong. Tal has done some good analysis on this move to show that white is perfectly equal in every line though. } (14. c5!? { The engine disagrees with Tal and claims that this space-gaining idea is best, even though it does "reduce the front" of the war. } 14... Qb8 15. b4 f6! 16. Nd3 Bf5 $14 { With e5 coming, black is not without any play. Tal rejected c5 for this reason. }) 14... dxc4!? { Botvinnik decides to give up the center in order to better activate his pieces. } (14... Qb4!? 15. Nxc6! { Tal's proposed plan is tricky and forcing. } (15. Bc3!? Qxa5 16. Bxa5 b6 17. cxd5 $10 { "With a definite edge in the endgame." }) 15... bxc6 16. Qxa6 dxc4 17. Ba3 Qb6 18. Qxb6 axb6 19. bxc4 $14 { White is up a pawn, but the resulting position dries out quickly after: } 19... Bxd4! 20. Bxe7 Rd7 21. Bg5 Bb2 22. Rxd7 Bxc1 23. Rd8+ Rxd8 24. Bxd8 Bxc4 25. Bxc6 Bxa2 26. Bxb6 $10) (14... Bxe5!? 15. dxe5 Qb4 16. Bc3! (16. Qxb4?! Nxb4 17. a3? Na2! 18. Ra1 dxc4! 19. Rxd8+ Rxd8 20. Rxa2? Rd2! $19 { Black quickly regains the piece. }) 16... Qxa5 17. Bxa5 b6 18. cxd5 cxd5 19. Bc3 $10 { "But of course it is not easy to decide on giving up the DSB." }) 15. Nxc4 (15. bxc4? Bxe5 16. dxe5?? (16. Qxe5 Qxe5 $17) 16... Qxd1+ 17. Rxd1 Rxd1+ 18. Bf1 Bh3 $19) 15... Qc7?! { Naturally Botvinnik seeks to exchange pieces with a more cramped position. } (15... Qb4!? $10 { A more forcing way to exchange pieces. } 16. Ba3!? (16. Bc3!? Qxa5 17. Nxa5 Rc7 $10) 16... Qxa5 17. Nxa5 Rc7 $10) 16. Qe1! { Out of range of all of black's minor pieces, the queen helps support the center. Tal has no interest in exchanging queens. } 16... Qb8 17. e4?! { The engine points out that Botvinnik's defensive resources here are enough. It instead recommends the amazingly patient: } (17. Ba1! { Now both Bxc4 and c5 are ruled out forever. } 17... Bxc4?! (17... Nc7!? 18. e4 $14) 18. bxc4 c5? 19. d5 $16 { Playable, now that the DSB is defended. }) 17... Bxc4! { "A difficult, but correct decision." } 18. Rxc4 (18. bxc4?! c5! { Botvinnik's point. } 19. e5 cxd4 20. Bxd4 e6 $15) 18... Nc7?! (18... c5! { Once again, this freeing move is correct. } 19. e5!? cxd4 20. Rcxd4 $10 { "The inferior position of white's queen bishop is fully compensated by the active king bishop." Importantly, Nc5 is not an outpost. }) 19. Bh3!? { Tal directly prevents Ne6 after nearly 20 minutes thought. } (19. h4! { A more aggressive way to prevent Ne6. Moreover, the bishop may not need to go to h3 in every variation. } 19... h5?! (19... Ne6?! 20. e5! $16 { h5 is coming and black's about to be attacked by every piece after the thematic Bc1! reroute. }) (19... e6!? 20. h5 $14 { There was no need to commit the bishop to h3 after all. }) 20. Bh3! $14) (19. Bc1!? { Tal really wanted to pull the trigger on this reroute. } 19... Ne6? (19... b5! 20. Rxc6 Bxd4 $10 { Tal doesn't mention this liquidating maneuver which should actually be the critical line. }) (19... Nb5?! { Tal believed this was the only move and spends a lot time discussing the ramifications here after } 20. Bh3 e6?! (20... Nxd4! 21. Bxc8 Qxc8!? (21... Nf3+?! 22. Kh1 Qxc8 23. Rxd8+ Qxd8 24. Qe2 Nd4 25. Qd3 e5 $16 { For some reason, Tal spends a while trying to justify not playing 19. Bc1 because he didn't know how to win this "won" position.
As always, this is way too deep, and not the critical line. Moreover, you shouldn't reject a winning line by hoping you could obtain "a larger advantage in the further course of the game." }) 22. Qe3 c5 $10 { A better version of inserting the checks. }) 21. Bf4 Qa8 22. d5 $16) 20. d5! $16) 19... e6 20. Bc1 { Rerouting to f4. } 20... Qa8! { The queen is well-placed on a8, surprisingly. Now Bf4 does nothing, and so d5 is not playable. } (20... Nb5?! 21. Bf4 $16 { Transposing to the aforementioned line. }) 21. Bg5 (21. Bf4?! b5! $10) 21... Re8 (21... Rd7!? { Tal thinks this looks wrong to put both bishops opposite the LSB, but the engine isn't impressed. } 22. Qe3 (22. d5?! cxd5 23. exd5 Rxd5! (23... Nxd5?? 24. Bxe6! $18) 24. Bxe6 (24. Rxd5?! Nxd5 25. Bxe6?? Re8! $19) 24... Nxe6 25. Rxd5 Nxg5 26. Rxg5 Rxc4 27. bxc4 f5! $10 { Amazingly, the rook is trapped and white has no advantage at all. }) 22... Rf8! $14 { and d5 is overrated. }) 22. Qd2 f5!? { Fighting back against white's wayward bishop pair. } 23. Bh6? { It's anti-positional to trade off one of the bishops when you have the bishop pair and Tal knew it. He just felt that the g7 bishop was stronger than the g5 bishop even though that's not truly the case. Played after 15 minutes. } (23. Re1! { was actually strongest, so as to further pressure the potentially backwards e6 pawn. } 23... fxe4? (23... a5!? 24. Bg2! { threatening exf5 or d5. } 24... fxe4 25. Rxe4 $16 { Bh3 again is always playable, and black's backwards e6 pawn is an eye sore. }) 24. Rxe4 $16 { Black's knight cannot use the d5 square because it must protect e6. }) (23. f3?! Nb5 $14 { Tal notes that black's threat of Nd6 is annoying. }) (23. exf5!? exf5 24. g4!? fxg4 25. Bxg4 Nd5! 26. Bxc8 Qxc8 $10 { Tal felt that black's position was easier to play during the game than white's. Indeed, black has full compensation for the exchange. }) (23. a4!? { Another useful move that keeps the tension simply highlights how passive black's position is. } 23... fxe4?! 24. Re1 $16) 23... Bxh6 24. Qxh6 Re7 (24... fxe4?! 25. Re1 $16 { As always, the e6 pawn now becomes an immediate issue. }) 25. Re1 Rf8!? { Protecting against potential sacrifices on f5. Botvinnik is next prepared to bring his queen back into the game from her cell on a8. } (25... Rce8!? $10 { Passive, but strong too. Qd8 is coming, as in the game. }) 26. Rc5 { Played after 20 minutes. Both players have less than 30 minutes to play 14 moves, and so once again Tal is trying to use time pressure in order to force Botvinnik to have to waste time calculating. } 26... Qd8 27. Re5 Ref7 { Botvinnik gets out of the pin on the e file and prepares to capture d4. } (27... Qxd4!? 28. exf5 gxf5 29. Bxf5 Ref7 30. R5e4 Qf6 31. Qxf6 Rxf6 32. Bxe6+ Nxe6 33. Rxe6 Rxf2 34. Re7 $10 { A drawn, but favorable endgame for white. }) 28. Qd2 Qd6 { Since white's LSB is biting on granite, he finds a newly weakened diagonal to pounce on instead. } 29. Bf1! { Bc4 is coming, with more pressure on e6. } 29... Rd7 { A good move, but it took Botvinnik most of his remaining time to come up with it. } 30. exf5 (30. Bc4?? Qxe5 $19) 30... Rxf5 (30... exf5? 31. Bc4+ Kg7 32. b4 $16 { b5 is coming to undermine black's queenside. The bishop is stronger than the knight, and both of white's rooks are stellar on the e file. }) 31. R5e4!? { Keeping more pieces on the board. Botvinnik has 9 minutes to make time control. } (31. Rxf5!? exf5 32. Bc4+ Kg7 33. Qc3 $10 { d4 is tactically defended, and so black needs to play super carefully here still. }) 31... Rf6?! { Missing a chance to liquidate, Botvinnik plays a solid move quickly. } (31... Rd5! { Simplifying into an equal endgame. } 32. Bc4?! (32. R1e3!? { This clever engine move keeps winning chances alive. } 32... c5! (32... Rxd4?? 33. Rxd4 Qxd4 34. Rd3 $18) 33. dxc5 Rxd2 34. cxd6 R7xd6 $10 { Also equal, but at least white can try and win this Fischer endgame. }) 32... Rxd4 33. Rxd4 Qxd4 34. Qxd4 Rxd4 35. Bxe6+ Nxe6 36. Rxe6 $10 { Tal's line is clearly dead equal. }) 32. h4! { Botvinnik has no time on his clock. Charge!
This position and time pressure is extremely reminiscent of Nepo - Ding, 2023 (7) except with roles reversed. https://lichess.org/VPr1aih5 } 32... Kg7?! { Inconsistent. If black is going to capture on h5, the king is better placed on g8 - leaving g7 open for a rook. } 33. h5 gxh5!? { Probably correct, since now white needs to spent a tempo or two to recapture the pawn. If white's rook leaves the 4th rank, black can sometimes offload the h pawn with h4 himself and ruin white's kingside shelter. } 34. Rh4!? (34. Qg5+!? Rg6 35. Qxh5 Nd5 $14) 34... Kg8 { 3 minutes remaining to make 6 moves. } 35. Bd3!? { Tal focuses the bishop towards black's king. } (35. Be2! { The most precise move - preventing Rdf7. } 35... Rdf7?! 36. Bxh5 Rxf2?? 37. Bxf7+ $18) 35... Rg7? { An extremely natural move, but a mistake nonetheless. } (35... Rdf7! $10 { Technically, black is fine here, but divining that with no time on your clock is near impossible. }) 36. Re5! { Both h pawns are in white's sights. } 36... Rff7 37. Qh6?! { Tal throws his queen in the mix, but honestly you would want to be leading the attack with your rooks and bishops, so this is not the most precise. } (37. Rexh5!? $16 { Simple and good. Black's pieces are too passive now. }) 37... Qe7! 38. Rexh5 Nd5 { Finally, Botvinnik gets his knight back into the game. It stands well on a strong outpost, but it is only one good piece compared to Tal's four. } 39. Qd2! { Fixing his previous mistake. There's no immediate win, and the queen is better as a supporting actress. } (39. Bxh7+?? Rxh7 40. Rg4+ Kh8 41. Qg6 Nf6! $19 { Black holds and there's nothing for the sacrificed piece. }) 39... Nf6 40. Rh6 Qd6?! { Played with seconds on his clock. Botvinnik had barely reached time control, and had a rotten position. } (40... Nd7! $16 { Botvinnik's second later showed that putting the knight on f8 would have been extremely tough to crack. Still, white remains better. }) 41. Rf4 { Tal played this move after only 3 minutes. Once more, he rejects the option to seal a move. Botvinnik thought for 40 minutes before sealing his move... } 41... Qf8?! { The sealed move is passive, and Tal didn't think much of it during his analysis. However, it was not the only option available to black, and so Tal spent the entire night analyzing lots of variations. The following is Tal's home analysis. } (41... Nd7!? { Tal decided this was black's best bet. } 42. Rxf7 Kxf7 43. Bxh7! c5?! (43... Nf6!? 44. Qd3 $16 { although once again white's bishop is offsides on h3. Compare this with the Ng4 variation. }) 44. Qe2! $16) (41... Ng4!? { The most active move is probably best. Tal "refuted it" with } 42. Bxh7+ Kf8! 43. Rxf7+ Rxf7? (43... Kxf7! 44. Rh4 { Tal thought this would be clearly winning, but in fact black has some serious counterplay after: } 44... Nf6! 45. Qd3 Qa3! $14 { The black queen is super active, and white's bishop on h7 is just a target. }) 44. Rg6! Rxf2 45. Rg8+! Kf7 46. Qd3! $18) (41... e5?! { "Curious variations arise" } 42. dxe5!? (42. Rf5?? Qxd4! $10 { [%cal Gg7g3] }) 42... Qxe5 43. Rhxf6!? (43. Rf5! { The move Tal preferred. } 43... Qa1+!? (43... Qd4!? 44. Kg2 $16) 44. Kg2 $16) 43... Rxf6 44. Bc4+ Rgf7! 45. Qd8+ Kg7 46. Bxf7! Kxf7! (46... Rxf4?? 47. Qg8+ Kh6 48. gxf4 $18) 47. Qh8!! $16 (47. Qd7+?! Qe7 48. Rxf6+?! Kxf6 49. Qxe7+?! Kxe7 $10)) (41... Qe7?! { Passive. } 42. Qe2 $16) (41... Qd8?! { Passive. } 42. Qe2 $16) 42. Qe3 Nd5 43. Rxf7 Qxf7 44. Qe5! { Played after 15 minutes. Tal keeps the queens on the board because of how open black's king is. The threat is Rxe6. } (44. Qxe6?! Qxe6 45. Rxe6 $16 { Not as convincing. }) 44... Nc7 45. Qc5! { Black is unable to cope with a queen poking around on the queenside all of a sudden. } 45... Qf3 { This move was played nearly instantly, so presumably we're still in Botvinnik's home analysis. Unfortunately for him, black finally gets active, but white has a forced win. } (45... a6? 46. Qa7! Ne8? (46... Nd5? 47. Qb8+ Qf8 48. Bxh7+! $18) 47. Rxe6! Qxe6 48. Bc4 $18) 46. Bxh7+! { Perhaps Botvinnik was hoping that Tal would not find this shot. } 46... Rxh7 47. Qg5+! Kh8 (47... Rg7?! 48. Qd8+ Qf8 49. Rh8+ $18) 48. Qd8+ Kg7 49. Rxh7+ Kxh7 50. Qxc7+ Kg6 51. Qxb7 { Up two pawns. "Now the win is a matter of technique." } 51... Qe4 (51... Qd1+?! 52. Kg2 Qxd4 53. Qxc6 $18) 52. Qa6! (52. Qxa7?! Qe1+ 53. Kg2 Qe4+ 54. Kh2 Qf3 55. Kg1 $18 { It's hard to extricate the black queen. }) 52... Qb1+ 53. Kg2 Qe4+ 54. Kf1 Qb1+ 55. Ke2 Qc2+ 56. Kf3! { Black has very few checks remaining. } 56... Qf5+ 57. Ke3 Qg5+ 58. Ke2 Qh5+ 59. Kd2 Kf6!? (59... Qg5+!? 60. Kd1 Qg4+ 61. Kc2 $18 { There are no good checks anymore, and white is winning. }) 60. Qxc6 Qa5+ 61. Qc3 Qxa2+ 62. Ke3 { As long as there is no perpetual, trading pawns brings the game closer to a winning queen endgame. } 62... Kf7 63. d5! { Fully blasting lines open to black's king! Now white attains two connected passed pawns. } 63... exd5 (63... e5?! 64. Qc4 $18 { [%cal Gd5d6] }) 64. Qc7+ Ke6 65. Qc6+ Ke7!? (65... Ke5!? 66. f4+! Kf5 67. Qxd5+ $18) 66. Qxd5 { The f and g pawns will decide the game. As long as white keeps his queen centralized, there's no real way to go wrong now. } 66... Qa1 67. Qe4+ Kf7 68. Kf4 Qc1+ 69. Kg4 Qa1 70. Qd5+ Kf8 71. Kf5 Qb1+ 72. Kf6 $18 { 1-0 White wins.
Tal takes a 2 point lead over Botvinnik again. } 1-0


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.04.12"]
[Round "12"]
[White "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D32"]
[Opening "Tarrasch Defense: Symmetrical Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 12: Botvinnik - Tal, Semi-Tarrasch"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/dPMxozwD"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Tal remarks how this is a complicated game with many mistakes. "I only want to add that extraordinarily tense, full-blooded struggles that are absolutely without any mistakes are only to be found in distance interplanetary chess tournaments..." otherwise known as modern chess at the 2800+ level. }
1. c4 Nf6 2. d4 { Botvinnik continues to avoid the English proper. } 2... e6 3. Nf3 { Avoiding the Nimzo again. } 3... d5 { Tal decides to try out the QGD now too. With the knight on f3 instead of possibly e2, Tal already notes that white doesn't get much from the exchange variations. } 4. Nc3 (4. cxd5!? exd5 5. Nc3 c6 { Bf5 is coming in every variation. } 6. Qc2!? (6. Bg5!? h6 7. Bh4 Bf5! $10) 6... g6! 7. Bg5 Be7! 8. e3 Bf5 $10 { Black occupies this all-important diagonal before white. }) 4... c5!? { Tal opts for the Semi-Tarrasch. } (4... c6!? { If Tal had played this match 30 years later, I think he would have found the semi-slav the perfect choice for his swashbuckling style. }) 5. e3!? (5. cxd5!? Nxd5 6. e3 $10 { Botvinnik's usual choice. He won a masterful game against Alekhine in 1938 ( https://lichess.org/6TBRNDr6 ), of which the starting position of the endgame is used by the Chess Dojo training program as a sparring position. }) 5... Nc6 6. a3! { The classical way to play this position. Rotweli - Rubinstein, for instance, featured a masterful game by black when white did not know this idea. } 6... Bd6!? { By developing this bishop, black practically begs white to saddle him with an IQP. } (6... a6!? { "does not equalize the game in view of the strong move" } 7. b3! $10 { Of course this does not hold up to modern analysis. Still, Korobov has championed this for white in recent years with only reasonable results. } { Korobov, A. - Mamedov, Rau, 0-1, Kupreichik Mem Open 2018, https://lichess.org/mbEyQec1 }) 7. dxc5 { "White does not refuse the obliging invitation to win two tempi." } 7... Bxc5 8. b4 Bd6 9. Bb2 O-O 10. cxd5 { Correct. And yet Botvinnik has already spent 31 minutes to barely get out of the opening. } (10. Qc2!? { Tal was white in this position against Aronin, but after } 10... a5?! (10... Qe7! $10 { José Queraltó, Daniel - Laine, Jari, 1/2-1/2, EU/C2021/sf  11, https://lichess.org/sBkekZI0 }) 11. b5 Ne5 12. Nxe5 Bxe5 { "White's opening turned out to be rather innocuous." Meanwhile, the engine thinks that white has something serious here with: } 13. Na4! Bxb2 14. Qxb2 $14 { because black's LSB is so awful, and playing b6 just creates an accessible target. }) 10... exd5! { If you're going to get an IQP, at least make sure that you keep more pieces on the board. Since Botvinnik typically loves playing with the IQP, Tal notes that he "was psychologically satisfied with the results of the opening since at certain moments Botvinnik might be playing 'against himself.' " } (10... Nxd5?! 11. Nxd5 exd5 $14 { A better version for white. More pieces have been traded. }) 11. Nb5! { Focusing on the d4 blockading square, with tempo. } 11... Bb8 { Played after 11 minutes. Tal doesn't comment on this, but perhaps he wanted to focus on the kingside here. Thus, rather than play the "meek" Be7, he goes for activity. } 12. Be2!? (12. Nbd4!? { Completing the maneuver gives Tal an interesting option. } 12... Ne5!? { Tal's line. } 13. Nxe5 Bxe5 14. Nc6?! { Completely natural... except for: } 14... Bxb2!? 15. Nxd8 Bc3+! 16. Ke2 Rxd8 17. Rc1 d4! $10 { "with a sharp and probably not disadvantageous game for black." Completely correct! Indeed, this is another fascinating example of the depths Tal goes to spice up the position. Forget the IQP - this is a complete mess now. }) (12. Bxf6? Qxf6 13. Qxd5?? Qxa1+ $19 { It's important you cannot take the d pawn yet. }) 12... a5! { The b5 square is white's forever, but now the a8 rook gets into the game the only way it can. . } 13. bxa5 Nxa5 14. O-O { Tal's pieces are all active, although the position is a bit passive because white has a dream grip over the d4 square. } 14... Ra6 { Activating the rook. } 15. Be5! { The move "best of all depicts Botvinnik's style of play, which attempts in every game, first and foremost, to restrict his opponent's play." } (15. Bc3?! { The engine line } 15... Ne4 16. Qd4 Nxc3 17. Qxc3 Rc6 $10 { Why would black have any advantage here? }) (15. Bxf6!? Rxf6! { The point of Tal's rook lift. } (15... Qxf6? 16. Qxd5 $16) 16. Rc1 $14 { If white can trade off the bishop pair (preferably the DSB!), the IQP will certainly become a weakness rather than a strength. }) (15. Nbd4!? Nc4 16. Qc2 Re8!? $10 { Tal intended to sacrifice a pawn but snag the two bishops. }) 15... Bxe5 16. Nxe5 Re8?! { A simple move, activating one more pieces. } (16... Ne4! 17. Nd3 Nc4 { A slightly more accurate way to get counterplay. } 18. Nf4?! Ncd2! { and black is already better. } 19. Re1? Rh6! $17 { Qh4 is coming in next. }) 17. Nd3! { But now Botvinnik finds a precise maneuver to pressure the d pawn. } 17... Ne4 (17... Bd7!? { Another way to play - avoiding the complications of the game. } 18. Nd4 Nc4 19. Nf4 Ra4! $10) 18. Nf4! { The passive Be6 is not Tal's style, so he plunges on instead. } (18. Nb4? Rh6 19. Qxd5? Qh4! $19) 18... Re5!? { Highly suspicious play from Tal, but perhaps this sort of active defense is practically a better option. } (18... Be6!? $14 { White would surely start to take over now that black's pieces are disconnected and there are dark square weaknesses everywhere. }) 19. Rc1 Rh6 { Activity above all else. } 20. Nd4?! { Botvinnik, sensing danger around his king, postpones taking the d5 pawn for now and instead bolsters his kingside and center. He spent 24 minutes on this one move. } (20. Qd4! { Tal thought this move only forced a draw. } 20... Rg5 21. Nxd5? (21. Rfd1! { But in actual fact black's position is not nearly as sturdy as he thinks it is. f1 is free for the king and black has way over-committed himself to the kingside. } 21... Nb3!? 22. Qxe4! Nxc1 23. Bf3 $16 { A sharp continuation where white comes out on top. Botvinnik of course should have gone for this. }) 21... Rxg2+ 22. Kxg2 Qg5+ 23. Kh1 Rxh2+! $10 { Perpetual check coming next. }) (20. Nxd5? Nc6! { White's pieces "are hanging in air." } 21. Nf4 Qh4! 22. h3 Ng5! $10 { With a sacrifice incoming. } (22... g5? { Tal's line has a tactical flaw. } 23. Rxc6! (23. Nh5? { Tal's line continues like this. } 23... g4 24. hxg4?? (24. Nf4! gxh3 25. g3! $10 { And of course he missed this typical idea too. }) 24... Bxg4! 25. Bxg4 Rexh5! 26. Bxh5 Rxh5 $19) 23... bxc6 24. Qd8+ Kg7 25. Qd4! f6 26. Bc4! gxf4 27. Qa7+! Kg6 28. Qf7+ Kg5 29. Nd4 $18 { And white practically has a mating net. Of course, Botvinnik would never play like this, but still - it shows how weakening your king and assuming your opponent has to respond to your threats (even when they're slow like gxf4) is not usually a good idea. })) 20... Nc6!? { Tal opts for centralizing the silly knight on a5. } (20... Bd7!? { Tactically escaping Rxc8 ideas also makes sense. Qh4 is now an idea at the perfect moment. }) 21. g3?! { Another solid, albeit passive move from Botvinnik. I'm sure Tal was feeling elated here that white was not bothering to calculate the most active options available. } (21. Nf3! { Simple chess. } 21... Rf5 22. g4? { "wins the exchange." Obviously Botvinnik would never consider such an reckless option. } (22. Bd3! $16 { Simple chess. Rxc6 followed by Bxe4 is the threat. Black needs to be careful here. } 22... Qd6!? { Tal does mention this move, with the idea of g5-g4, breaking through to h2. But once more this is quite slow, and white has many options available to him, such as: } 23. Qa4! g5!? 24. Rfd1! gxf4 25. Bxe4! $16) 22... Rxf4! 23. exf4 Bxg4 $17 { "Black has a position that promises the initiative." }) (21. Nxc6?! bxc6! $10 { There's no reason black is worse here. The dark squares are covered by the beautiful knight on e4. }) 21... g5! { Energetic play is required to prevent Botvinnik from being able to target the d pawn freely. } 22. Nd3 Re8 23. Bg4! { Once more, Botvinnik seeks to prevent an attack. Furthermore, this nice move targets white's kingside weaknesses on the light squares. } 23... Bxg4 24. Qxg4 Nxd4 25. exd4 Qf6!? { Stiring up trouble again. } (25... Ra6!? $10 { "To play such a move after the move g5 would not be logical." The engine of course has no reservations. }) (25... f5?! 26. Qd1! $14 { There is no attack here, and white's knight is a monster of one of the main available outposts. }) 26. Ne5 Nd2 { Both knights are jumping around the position, so both players should seek to "get rid of their unwelcome guest," even at the price of the exchange. } 27. Rfd1 { A quiet approach from Botvinnik played after 15 minutes. Already, Botvinnik has to make 13 moves in 15 minutes... } (27. f4?! { A critical way to sacrifice the exchange. } 27... Nxf1 28. Rxf1 { The right idea, but Tal spotted the important response: } (28. fxg5? Nxh2! 29. Qd7! Nf3+! 30. Nxf3 Qe6 (30... Rh1+? 31. Kf2! (31. Kxh1?? Qxf3+ 32. Kh2 Re2+ 33. Kg1 Qg2#) 31... Rh2+! 32. Kg1 Rg2+! 33. Kxg2 Re2+ 34. Kh3 Qxf3 35. Qd8+! Kg7 36. Qf6+ Qxf6 37. gxf6+ Kxf6 { "A difficult endgame for white." }) 31. Ne5 Rh5! $17 { Black consolidates the exchange. }) 28... Rg6! $15 { After which the attack has been repulsed. }) (27. h4!? { Sacrificing the exchange in a safer manner. } 27... Nxf1 28. Rxf1 Qg7 29. hxg5 Rhe6 $10) 27... Rxe5! 28. Rxd2! { With little time on the clock, Botvinnik plays for simplicity. } (28. dxe5!? Nf3+ 29. Kf1 Qa6+ (29... Nxe5!? { A more double-edged continuation is of course what Tal would have considered. } 30. Qc8+ Kg7 31. h3 $14) 30. Kg2 Rxh2+ 31. Kxf3 Qxa3+ 32. Ke2 Qa2+! 33. Kd3 Qa6+! $10 { With a forced draw. }) 28... Re4 29. Qc8+?! { 11 minutes left, and Botvinnik offered a draw. Tal thinks the position is too sharp to accept, and plays on instantly. } (29. Qd7!? Qe7 30. Qxe7 Rxe7 $10 { Leads to a much clearer draw. }) 29... Kg7 30. Qxb7 { The pawn is mostly irrelevant. } 30... Qe6 (30... Reh4?? { An interesting idea that Tal considered that didn't work at all. } 31. gxh4 gxh4 32. Qxd5 Rg6+ 33. Kf1! $18 { And white's totally fine. }) 31. Rf1?? { Defends against Re1+ but allows several interesting options. } (31. Qb1! { Tal's suggestion stops Re1+ for good. }) 31... Re1?? { At least Tal thought for 5 minutes before pulling the trigger on this move. Tal still has 40 minutes before the time control, as opposed to Botvinnik's 9 minutes. } (31... Reh4! { Tal analyzed this idea last move, but it didn't work because an eventual Kf1->e2 allowed the white king to escape. Now, however, white's mated himself! } 32. gxh4 Qg4+ 33. Kh1 Qf3+ 34. Kg1 gxh4 $19 { Rg6+ is unstoppable. }) 32. Qb5 Qh3 33. f3! Qe6!? { Tal continued making moves here thinking he wasn't even down a pawn. He only discovered this fact after reaching the time control. } (33... Rb6!? 34. Qd3 Rbb1 35. Rf2 Rxf1+ 36. Rxf1 Rb2 37. Rf2 Rxf2 38. Kxf2 Qxh2+ 39. Kf1! Qxg3 $10 { Tal considered this forcing variation, only to recognize that he was still a pawn down from white's move 30. The best black has is a draw. }) 34. Rf2 Rf6 35. Rxe1 Qxe1+ 36. Kg2 g4! 37. Qd3 h5! 38. Rf1 { Botvinnik has done well to defend solidly and catch up to Tal on the clock. } 38... Qe6 39. fxg4!? { Essentially admits that this will be a drawn position. Winning chances with only queens on the board (and a super weak king at that!) are essentially nonexistent. } (39. h4!? { Tal's suggestion keeps more life in the position for white. }) 39... Rxf1 40. Kxf1 hxg4 41. a4?! { White's sealed move was prepared over 15 minutes. Tal believes that it should lead to a quick draw. } (41. Kg2! { Tal was convinced that this was the only way to try for an advantage. His analyzed line at home went: } 41... Qb6 42. h4 Qb2+ 43. Kf1 Qa1+!? (43... f5! { Forces a draw. } 44. Qxf5 Qxd4 $10) 44. Ke2 Qb2+ 45. Qd2 Qxa3 46. Qg5+ Kf8 47. Qxg4 Qb2+ 48. Kf3 Qc3+ 49. Kg2 Qd2+ 50. Kh3 Qf2! { Black prepares a perpetual with Qf1+. } 51. Qd1! { A shock to Tal at home. } (51. Qf4?! Qxf4! 52. gxf4 f5 $10 { The h pawn alone is nothing. }) (51. Qd7?! Qf1+ 52. Kg4 Qe2+ 53. Kh3 Qf1+ $10 { The perpetual. }) 51... f5!? 52. Qd3! Kg7! 53. g4! f4!? (53... fxg4+!? 54. Kxg4 Qg1+?? (54... Kh8!! { An improvement on Tal's analysis. There is no way for white to make progress without dropping the d pawn with check. } 55. Kh5!? Qf7+ 56. Kg4 Qf2 $10) 55. Kh5! { Zugzwang! }) 54. h5 { "White creates an unpleasant mating threat." } 54... f3! { But this is totally fine for black after all. } 55. Qg6+ Kf8 56. h6 Qg2+ $10) 41... Qb6 42. Kf2 Qb4?! (42... Qb2+! 43. Ke3 Qc1+ 44. Qd2 Qb1 45. Kf4 Kf6! $10 { White's king is going nowhere. } 46. Kxg4?! Qf5+ 47. Kh4 Qh7+ 48. Kg4 Qf5+ $10) 43. Ke3! Qxa4 44. Kf4! { Botvinnik returns the a pawn and launches an attack on black's naked king while the queen is in Siberia. } 44... Qa2!? 45. Qe3! { Botvinnik knows that holding on to all the pawns is impossible, but now there's a good chance for an endgame attack against black's king. } 45... Qxh2 46. Qe5+ Kf8 47. Qd6+ Kg7 48. Qxd5 (48. Qe5+ Kf8 49. Qxd5 $10 { Tal believes this is a slight improvement for white since now the king is worse on f8. }) 48... Qf2+ 49. Kxg4 f5+ { Forcing more pawn trades. } 50. Kg5 (50. Qxf5 Qxd4+ $10) 50... Qxg3+ 51. Kxf5 Qg6+ 52. Kf4 Qf6+ 53. Ke3 Kf8 54. Kd3 Qf1+?! (54... Ke7 $10 { The simplest approach. Just get the king in front of the pawn and all pawn endgames are drawn! }) 55. Ke4 Qg2+ (55... Ke7 $10) 56. Ke5 Qg5+ 57. Ke6 Qe7+ 58. Kf5 Qc7! { Giving a square to the king on e7. } (58... Qh7+?! 59. Ke5 Qh5+? 60. Kd6! Qh2+ 61. Kd7 Qh7+ 62. Kd8 Qh4+ 63. Kc7 Qe7+ 64. Kc8! Qe8+ 65. Qd8 $18) 59. Qa8+ Ke7! (59... Kf7!? 60. Qa2+ Kf8 61. Qd5 { A difficult attempt at a Zuzgwang compared to the game. } 61... Ke7?? (61... Qb6! $10) 62. Qe5+! $18) 60. Qe4+ Kd8 { With the king finally blockading the pawn, there should be no more issues. } 61. Qh4+ Kc8 62. Qh8+ Kb7 63. Qe5 Qf7+ 64. Ke4 Qg6+ 65. Qf5 Qd6! { A good way to ice the game. The only way to make progress is remove black's queen from d6. The only way to do that is offer to trade. All king and pawn endgames will be drawn if the black king can get to d6 or d7 in time. } 66. Qf7+ Kc8 67. Qf5+ Kd8 68. Qa5+ Ke8 69. d5 Kd7 70. Qa7+ Kd8 71. Qa8+ Kd7 72. Kf5 Ke7 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { Finally, both players reached the second time control, and decided to draw the game rather than play any further meaningless checks. } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.04.14"]
[Round "13"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A30"]
[Opening "English Opening: Symmetrical Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 13: Tal - Botvinnik, Symmetric English"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/4rgQ7xM5"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ This game lasted less than an hour, mostly because both players were exhausted after the intense games 10-12. Interestingly enough, when Tal left the theater after this insta-draw, he saw a play being put on about the match, the thirteenth game in particular, and chess robots.

"I only want to stress that, fortunately for the lovers of this art, the appearance of chess 'robots' is not imminent. Chess players are people with human characteristics and human weaknesses and to turn a man's brain into a machine or even allow it to become flawless is not only a hopeless, but a useless task."

Quite possibly one of the most incorrect takes of the entire book! Any chess player in the 21st century knows that all chess players work closely with machines that never tire, never blunder, and are in fact far superior at this game than any man. }
1. c4!? { Having switched away from 1. e4, and succeeded with 1. d4, Tal wants to probe with 1. c4. } 1... c5 { Botvinnik apparently was opting for symmetrical play whenever possible. } 2. Nf3 (2. Nc3!? Nf6 3. g3!? (3. Nf3!? { More common now, to prevent such an idea. } 3... d5!? 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. e4! Nb4 6. Bc4 Nd3+ 7. Ke2 $14 { Transposing directly into a sharp reversed Sicilian line. }) 3... d5 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Nc7 6. d3 e5 $10 { A normal position in the English. } { Iturrizaga Bonelli, Eduardo - Firouzja, Alireza, 1/2-1/2, Chessable Masters Prelim, 2021, https://lichess.org/BhaANh7J }) 2... Nf6 3. g3 b6!? (3... d5!? { Tries to ice the game, but white has: } 4. cxd5 Nxd5 5. Bg2 Nc6 6. d4 $10 { transposing to the Catalan. } { Carlsen, Magnus - Topalov, Veselin, 1/2-1/2, Norway Chess, 2013, https://lichess.org/JNf4bkVj }) (3... g6!? 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. O-O O-O 6. d4 $10 { A Dragon type position. Botvinnik is out of his element here though. }) 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. O-O g6!? (5... e6!? 6. d4 cxd4 7. Qxd4 Nc6 8. Qf4 $10 { Some pressure here. A very Ulf Andersson type position for white. Neither player would be happy here to be honest, but Tal is always allowed to play for a draw, up 2 points in the match. }) 6. d4!? (6. Nc3 Bg7 7. d3!? O-O 8. e4 $10 { A Botvinnik position as white. Tal only tried this out a year later against Teschner. }) 6... cxd4 7. Qxd4 { A good option, but only if white knows what they are doing. Tal thought they were in the e6 variation mentioned above. } (7. Nxd4 Bxg2 8. Kxg2 { Theory at the time mentioned this line of play as what white should do to get a minimal advantage. The engine isn't impressed after: } 8... Qc8! $10) 7... Bg7 8. Nc3 Nc6!? (8... O-O?! 9. Qh4! $14 { A big potential attack is coming on black's king. }) (8... d6!? { Is the main recommendation at the top level today. } 9. Rd1 Nbd7! 10. Be3 $10 { Caruana, F. - Karjakin, Sergey, 1/2-1/2, 30th ECC Open 2014, https://lichess.org/1vWMOJyf }) 9. Qh4?! (9. Qf4 $14 { As in the previous line is of course correct. } { Andreikin, Dmitry - Ivanchuk, Vassily, 1/2-1/2, EU-Cup 28th, 2012, https://lichess.org/X244ufE9 }) 9... h6! 10. Nd5!? (10. Qf4! $14 { Apparently losing one more tempo and claiming h6 is a bit of a weakness is technically playable. Seems ridiculous to a human though. }) 10... e6 { Forces white to waste a few tempi, but in such a symmetric position, "that has only a symbolic effect." } (10... Na5! { The most testing move. } 11. Nd2! (11. Nxf6+? Bxf6 12. Qg4 Rc8 13. Nd2 Bxg2 14. Kxg2 Qc7 $17 { The c pawn is a problem. }) 11... Rc8 12. Rb1! $10 { Praggnanandhaa, R. - Ding Liren, 1/2-1/2, Chessable Masters KO 2022, https://lichess.org/a3vwMYJO } { Tal thought this was the only way forward. That is correct. }) 11. Nxf6+ Qxf6 12. Qxf6 Bxf6 { If white can finish development smoothly and not lose the c pawn, then white can possibly push for an advantage. } 13. Rb1! Na5 { Black tries to use his advantage in development to prevent white from getting out of the opening alive, but white is OK after: } 14. b3! Be4 15. Bb2! { And white's just in time to get out of the opening alive. } 15... Bxb2 (15... Bxb1?? 16. Bxf6 $18 { The rook and bishop are both hanging. }) 16. Rxb2 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { White offered a draw with this recapture. Fine, given Tal's notes about how exhausted he was before this game, but obviously the fans were not impressed. } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.04.19"]
[Round "14"]
[White "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E24"]
[Opening "Nimzo-Indian Defense: Sämisch Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 14: Botvinnik - Tal, Saemisch Nimzo Indian"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/rUR0DEpj"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ The match has been going on for more than a month now, and both competitors are playing slightly worse than they were at the beginning of the match.

Before the game, Tal predicted that Botvinnik would have to bring back the Saemisch Nimzo-Indian if he wanted to push for an advantage. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 { Botvinnik once more allows the Nimzo-Indian. } 3... Bb4 4. a3!? { And repeats the Saemisch! Tal came prepared. "This move is in complete accord with the forecast from the 'Riga Weather Bureau.' " haha classic stuff. } 4... Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 Ne4!? { "Probably the move is not good enough to equalize against theoretical recommendations, but its moral fiber also cannot be denied." } 6. Nh3!? { A sensible move, preparing f3 in some lines, played after 13 minutes. Tal and Taimanov think that this move isn't best, and that the line chosen with e3 in game 20 of this match is superior. } (6. f3?? Qh4+ 7. g3 Nxg3 $17) (6. Qc2!? f5 7. e3 b6 8. Bd3 Bb7 (8... O-O! 9. Bxe4 fxe4 10. Qxe4 Nc6! $15 { with Ba6 coming, black has some play. }) (8... Ba6! { Tal's novelty. } 9. Bxe4?! fxe4 10. Qxe4 Bxc4! 11. Qxa8 Bd5! 12. Qxa7 Bxg2 $17 { Regaining the rook and black has a better kingside pawn structure.
For more information on how this fits into modern theory, see Game 20 of the match. }) 9. Ne2 Qh4!? { Taimanov's suggestion. } (9... O-O!? 10. O-O c5 $10 { Engine play - typical of the dutch. }) 10. O-O O-O 11. f3 Ng5 $10 { Taimanov claims equality for black. But Tal disagrees and says: } 12. Bd2! $14 { With possibly Be1 or Nf4 coming. Black's pieces are too scattered to create an attack. Tal is more correct than Taimanov. }) 6... c5 { While white's knight is sidelined, black can play in the center. } (6... Nxc3?? 7. Qc2 $18 { Trapping the knight. }) 7. e3!? (7. Qc2?! Qa5! 8. Bd2 d5 9. f3? Nxd2 10. Qxd2 dxc4 $17 { With b5 coming, black is better. Saemisch once played this way as white and got a rotten position. }) (7. d5!? $10 { Similar to the Ne4 variations of the Trompowsky. }) 7... Qa5 8. Bd2!? { Solid, but passive. Botvinnik only played this move after a further 16 minutes. } (8. Qc2!? d5!? $10 { Tal's idea. } (8... cxd4! 9. exd4 Nc6 $15 { Taking the initiative instantly. } { [%cal Gc6d4] })) 8... cxd4 { Tal believes this move is a draw offer because the endgame is totally equal. } 9. cxd4!? { Passively aiming for symmetry. "Practically an acceptance of a draw." } (9. exd4!? O-O 10. Bd3 Nxd2 11. Qxd2 e5! $10 { The position is sharper for both sides, but black should be fine here. }) 9... Nxd2 10. Qxd2 Qxd2+ 11. Kxd2 b6 12. Bd3 Ba6 { Poking at the c pawn, trying to provoke c5, after which white has no space advantage and the game is perfectly level. } 13. Rhc1!? (13. Be4!? { A forcing variation, but not a good one. } 13... Nc6 14. d5? exd5 15. cxd5 Na5 $17 { Putting more pawns on light squares and losing tempo isn't correct. }) 13... Nc6 14. Rab1 { White is fully developed, but the knight on h3 leaves a poor impression, so black is completely fine here on the queenside. } 14... Ke7! 15. c5 { Botvinnik tries to provoke a showdown before Tal can put rooks on the b and c files himself. } (15. d5?! Ne5 16. d6+ Kf6! { The d pawn is more of a weakness than a strength. } (16... Kxd6?? 17. c5+ bxc5 18. Bxa6 $18)) 15... Bxd3 16. Kxd3 Rab8! { Tal has only used 20 minutes to get to this position, but the liquidation on the queenside is now unavoidable. } 17. Rb5 bxc5 18. Rcxc5 a6! { Taking the important b file from white. } (18... Rxb5?! 19. Rxb5 $14 { Now white is the one who owns the b file. }) (18... h6!? $10) 19. Rxb8 Rxb8 20. Kc2 { Prevents a rook invasion. } 20... Rc8 $10 { Draw offered by Tal and declined by Botvinnik. } 21. Nf4 d6 22. Rc3 g5 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { Draw offered by Botvinnik and accepted by Tal. "The position could not be more drawn." Tal had used only 30 minutes to Botvinnik's 1 hr 40 min to secure an easy draw as black.
Critics rebuked the players as "gladiators leaving the scene, not having bathed ourselves in an ocean of blood." But Tal believes this was a well-fought game, even if it ended in a draw rather quickly. } 23. Nd3!? { If the game were to continue: } 23... Kd7 24. Nb4 Nxb4+ 25. axb4 Rxc3+ 26. Kxc3 Kc6 $10 1/2-1/2


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.04.21"]
[Round "15"]
[White "Mikhail Tal"]
[Black "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "B18"]
[Opening "Caro-Kann Defense: Classical Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 15: Tal - Botvinnik, Classical Caro Kann"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/uDNDYlhZ"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Tal decided to return to 1. e4 and his battle against the Caro Kann. His trainer absolutely vetoed his idea to repeat the piece sacrifice line from the 9th game. }
1. e4 c6 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. Bc4 { A new move order. In some cases, this just transposes. Otherwise, the idea is to avoid playing h4. } 6... e6!? { Black no longer has the e5 idea in some lines. } (6... Nf6 7. N1e2 e6 8. h4 h6 9. Nf4 Bh7 $10 { Transposing. }) 7. N1e2 Bd6!? (7... Nf6!? { A sharper move, played by Botvinnik in game 17. }) 8. h4! (8. Nf4?! { Probably transposes, but is less flexible. } 8... Nf6 9. h4 Qc7! $10) 8... h6 9. Nf4 { White is gaining a tempo on the other line. } 9... Bxf4 { Forced, if black does not want to lose a tempo. So now Tal gets the bishop pair because black opted to develop his bishops before the knights. } (9... Bh7?! 10. Ngh5! $16) 10. Bxf4 Nf6 11. Qd2!? { "A quieter continuation, but also not without poison." } (11. h5! Bh7 12. Qe2 $10 { Geller - Bagirov, 1960. }) 11... Nbd7!? { As always, Botvinnik goes for solidity. } (11... Nd5!? 12. O-O-O Nxf4 13. Qxf4 $10 { Tal was OK allowing this idea. }) 12. O-O-O!? { Sharpening up the play, but also allowing Botvinnik a second chance to snag his DSB. } (12. Be2!? Nd5?! (12... O-O 13. O-O! $14 { White has a good build up in the center, and black won't be able to break with c5 or e5 just yet. }) 13. Bd6 $14) 12... Nd5 { Botvinnik is happy to trade off the bishop pair. He has already used 40 minutes to Tal's 11. } 13. Rde1?! { Setting up a transparent trap. Tal made this artificial move in less than a minute. } (13. Bd6? N7b6! $17) (13. f3!? { A smarter option if you want to wait. The rook does not need to be moved from the d file. }) (13. Bb3!? N7b6 14. Be5! $14 { "White can cause some difficult on the kingside." }) 13... N7b6!? (13... Qf6?? 14. Bg5! $18 { The basic trap. }) (13... Nxf4! 14. Qxf4 O-O 15. h5 Bh7 { With Nf6 coming, probably white should place the rook back on the d file. } 16. Rd1 $15) 14. Bb3 Nxf4 15. Qxf4 Nd5 16. Qe5! { Annoyingly, the queen cannot be challenged (yet). } (16. Qd2?! Qc7! $10 { Qf4 is coming to seek more trades. }) 16... O-O { Botvinnik has now spent over an hour. } (16... Rg8? { Botvinnik's idea from game 5 does not work here. } 17. f4! $16 { [%cal Gf4f5] }) 17. Ne4! { Tempo, tempo, tempo. Even without the DSB, white has enough firepower to build up on the kingside. } (17. f4?! Re8! $15 { f5 is never happening and white has achieved nothing positive on the kingside besides creating light square weaknesses. }) 17... Qb8 { Of course, Botvinnik tries to deflate white's attack with a soothing queen trade. } (17... a5!? { If Tal were playing black, I assumed he'd opt for this counterattacking move instead. } 18. a4 Rb8!? $10 { [%cal Gb7b5] } (18... b5!? $10 { "transposes into positional lines" because black gives up control over the c5 square. A highly insightful comment that shows that Tal loves attacking but always looks at the game through a positional lens. })) 18. Nd6! { Tal is preparing to place his knight on e5 in the event of a queen trade. } 18... Rd8 (18... b5? { Nc4 cannot be prevented. } 19. h5 Bh7 20. Rh3 $16 { Rg3 is coming with a massive attack. } { [%cal Gh3g3] }) 19. Nc4 (19. h5!? Bxc2! { The move Tal didn't like. } (19... Qxd6?! 20. hxg6! fxg6 21. Qxe6+ Qxe6 22. Rxe6 $14 { "White has the better endgame." }) (19... Bxh5!? 20. Nxb7! Qxb7 21. Rxh5 $10) (19... Bh7? 20. Nxf7! Qxe5!? (20... Kxf7!? 21. Qxe6+ Kf8 22. Re3!! $16 { [%cal Ge3f3] } 22... Nxe3?? 23. Qf7#) 21. Nxe5 $16) 20. Nxf7! Qxe5 21. Rxe5! (21. Nxe5?! Bxb3! 22. axb3 $15) 21... Kxf7 22. Kxc2 $10) 19... Nb6?! { Botvinnik is really trying hard to prevent dxe5, but going backwards with the knight that clearly belongs on d5 isn't the way to go about it. } (19... Qxe5?! 20. Nxe5!? $10 { Getting to e5 with tempo is interesting. } (20. dxe5!? $10 { Focusing on the d6 outpost is also interesting. } { [%cal Gc4d6] })) (19... Bf5!? $10 { Getting out of Ne5 or h5 tempi is a smarter move. }) (19... Bh7!? $10 { Getting out of Ne5 or h5 tempi is a smarter move. }) 20. Qxb8 Raxb8 21. Ne5 Bh7 { And Botvinnik is down a tempo since his knight is misplaced. } 22. Rh3!? { Tal sacrifices the d pawn after only 3 minutes thought. "Strange as it may seem, probably at this very moment after the exchange of queens, white has his best chances for attack." } 22... Nd7!? { As usual, Botvinnik eschews complications against Tal, rather than relish them. Probably a poor decision given the fact that Tal is presenting plenty of opportunities in the midst of his tactical melees for black to equalize or even stand better. I believe that if Botvinnik engaged with these calculations more often, he might have won a few more games in this match. } (22... Rxd4!? { A dangerous move, given the attacking potential available to white. But objectively fine as this equalizes. } 23. Nxf7! Bf5! (23... Kxf7? 24. Bxe6+ Kf8!? (24... Kg6!? 25. Rg3+ Kf6! (25... Kh5?? 26. Rxg7 $18) 26. Rf3+ Ke7! (26... Kg6?? 27. Bf7#) 27. Bf5+ Kd6 28. Bxh7 $16) 25. Rf3+ Ke7 26. Bf5+ Kd6 27. Bxh7 $16) 24. Rf3 Bg4?! (24... Re4! { Not mentioned by Tal. Still, he did a reasonable job going broad instead of deep in this particular calculation. } 25. Rxe4 Bxe4 26. Re3 Kxf7 27. Rxe4 Nd5 $10) 25. Rg3! Kxf7 26. Rxg4! Rd6! (26... Rxg4? 27. Bxe6+ $18) 27. Rf4+ $14) 23. c3 { Allowing simplifications. } (23. Nxf7?? Kxf7 24. Bxe6+ Kf8 25. Rf3+ Nf6! 26. g4 Bg8! 27. g5 Re8! $19) 23... Nxe5?! (23... c5! { A better way to play - the freeing c5 pawn break can be played right away! } 24. Nxf7!? { However, now this tactical line is worth considering. } 24... Kxf7 25. Bxe6+ Kf8 26. Rf3+ Nf6 27. g4 cxd4! (27... Bg8? 28. g5 Re8 29. d5! $16 { One key difference between the lines is present here. White is not losing a piece after all. }) 28. g5 dxc3 29. gxf6 cxb2+ 30. Kxb2 gxf6 31. Rxf6+ Kg7 $10 { This line is scary to calculate, but white doesn't have anything in this simplified endgame. No doubt, Botvinnik calculated none of this in his 3 minute think on Nxe5. }) 24. Rxe5 b6 { White's only advantage is one of space, so black is trying to get in the freeing c5 break. } 25. Rhe3!? { Putting the pieces on the squares. } (25. Bc4!? { Korchnoi's improvement. } 25... Rbc8 26. b4 { Of course Korchnoi would seek to win a pawn and hold onto it at all costs... } 26... c5!! { Yet the engine has no such illusions! } 27. bxc5 bxc5 28. dxc5 Rb8! 29. Bb3 Rdc8 $10 { It's all about activity. Now white's queenside pawn structure is shattered and black is the one with rooks on the open files. }) 25... Rbc8 26. Bc4 Rc7!? { A moment of hesitation from Botvinnik. But he correctly judged in his 10 minute think that things were not so simple on the queenside after c5. } (26... c5!? { "Probably significantly stronger." } 27. dxc5!? (27. d5?! exd5!? (27... b5? 28. Bxb5 exd5 29. Re7 $16) 28. Rxd5 Rxd5 29. Bxd5 Kf8! $10 { Re7 is prevented, and this is an equal endgame. }) 27... Rxc5? (27... Kf8! $10 { "Now the rooks are misplaced on the closed e file and there is no way to prevent Rxc5 next." Maybe. The engine linkes: } 28. a3! Rxc5?! 29. Rxc5 bxc5 30. b4! cxb4 31. axb4 $14 { As a way to create a passed pawn on the c file. The important point being: } 31... Rc8?! 32. Be2 $16 { Kb2 and c4-c5 are coming next. } { [%cal Gc1b2,Gc3c4,Gc4c5] }) 28. Rxc5 bxc5 29. Re5 Rc8?! 30. Rxe6! $16) 27. b4 { Now that all of white's pieces are active, the c5 move doesn't equalize at all. } 27... Kf8! { Getting out of the constant Rxe6 motif. } (27... c5?! 28. dxc5 bxc5 29. Rxc5 (29. b5!? $14 { Positionally good too. }) 29... Rxc5 30. bxc5 Kf8!? (30... Rc8? 31. Rxe6! $16 { The key difference between the rook being on h3 or e3. }) 31. c6 $14) 28. g4! Bg8!? { Botvinnik continues to wait passively because he cannot figure out the complications. } (28... f6!? 29. Rf3! (29. Rxe6? Bg8! $17) 29... Bf5!? (29... c5!? $10 { The equalizing move according to the engine, but this position is way too sharp to play in practical terms, and Botvinnik is down to only 30 minutes again by move 28. }) 30. Bxe6! fxe5 31. Rxf5+ Ke8! (31... Ke7? 32. Rf7+ Kxe6 33. Rxc7 $16) 32. Rxe5 $14 { Tal completely nailed this line. }) 29. Bb3?! { Defending the bishop makes sense if you want to force through this f4 idea. But the c5 pawn break was the more crucial one to watch out for. } (29. f4? f6! 30. R5e4 Bh7! 31. Rxe6 Bg8! $15 { Again winning the exchange for little. }) (29. a3!? $14 c5? 30. dxc5 bxc5 31. b5 $14) 29... Bh7?! { A disgusting waiting move from Botvinnik. It took him a further 10 minutes to play this sad move so he's not really even doing a good job with his time management before the time control. } (29... c5! { Finally, this move makes the most sense. } 30. bxc5 bxc5 31. Rxc5 Rxc5 32. dxc5 Rc8 33. Rd3 { was Tal's idea. } 33... Ke7! 34. Ba4! Rxc5 35. Rd7+ Kf6 36. Kb2 { "with a significant advantage" except not at all true. } 36... g5! 37. h5!? (37. hxg5+!? Kxg5 38. Rxa7 Kxg4 $10 { How could black be worse with such an active king and a passed rooks pawn too? }) 37... a5! { All of black's base points are defended, and Bh7 is coming next next, so white should try: } 38. Bc2!? (38. Bb3!? Bh7 $10 { White has fixed pawns on light squares and so can't really be better here. }) 38... Rb5+! 39. Ka3 Rc5 40. Kb2 Rb5+ $10) 30. f4 Bg8 31. Kb2 { In expectation of c5 being played at the correct moment, the king is better on b2. } 31... Bh7 { At least Botvinnik is now able to move quickly. } (31... f6!? 32. R5e4 a5! { The engine shows some counterplay here for black. But this is hard to consider and certainly not going to be selected by Botvinnik while he's so low on time. } 33. a3 axb4 34. axb4 c5 35. dxc5 bxc5 36. b5 Rb7 37. c4 Rd2+ 38. Kc3 Rh2 $10 { Counterplay. }) 32. h5! Rdc8 { With no time to waste, as g5 is coming, Botvinnik decides to go all out for the c5 pawn break. } 33. Bc2!? Bg8!? { Tal gives this a double exclam. He was impressed with Botvinnik's evaluation that the bishop should stay on in order to minimize the effects of white's more active rooks. But in reality, the visually displeasing move is probably not better than just trading it off... if you calculate correctly.
Botvinnik is now ready to play f6, R5e4 and then c5 against anything. } (33... Bxc2!? 34. Kxc2 { The obvious line does leave white slightly better, but after: } 34... c5! 35. dxc5 bxc5 36. a3 Rb7 37. Kd2! (37. Kd3!? Rd7+ 38. Kc2 Rb7 39. Kb3 a5 $10 { No progress anywhere here. }) 37... Rd7+ 38. Rd3! Ke7 39. Rxd7+ Kxd7 40. Kd3 f6! 41. Re1 a6! $10 { Black is probably holding here too. }) 34. g5?! { After 20 minutes, Tal couldn't find anything better. } (34. a4! { In expectation of black's plan, this is certainly the best way forward. } 34... f6 35. R5e4 c5 36. dxc5! bxc5 37. b5 $16 { White's bishop will sit nicely on c4 after all. }) (34. Bb3!? Bh7 35. a4! $16 { The other way to play. It's debatable if the bishop is better on h7 or g8. }) 34... f6! 35. R5e4 c5! { Botvinnik goes for it at last, with 6 minutes on his clock to make 5 moves. } 36. Bb3? (36. dxc5! bxc5 37. b5 $16 { "Significantly stronger, with a great advantage on the queenside." }) 36... cxb4 { Of course, black activates all the rooks. } 37. cxb4 hxg5 { Not forced, but making more obvious moves just to get to the time control is a smart idea. } 38. fxg5 fxg5 39. Rg3 Rf7 40. Rxg5 Rf2+ { With one minute left, Botvinnik reaches the time control. } 41. Ka3 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { The game was adjourned here. Tal had thought this position looked good when he considered 36. Bb3. But at home, he saw that white had no advantage to speak of. The e pawn is no weaker than white's d pawn.
Tal offered a draw before resuming the game. } 41... Bf7!? (41... Rc7!? { Botvinnik's sealed move, determined after 30 minutes. } 42. Reg4 Rf5 43. Rxf5+ exf5 44. Rf4 Bxb3 45. Kxb3 Rf7 46. Kc4 Ke7 47. Kd5 Kf6 48. Kc6 Kg5 49. Rf1 f4 $10 { The f and d pawns are just as strong as each other. } { [%cal Gd4d8,Gf4f1] }) 42. Reg4 Rh2 43. Rxg7 Rxh5 $10 { Tal's analysis. Clear draw. } 1/2-1/2


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.04.23"]
[Round "16"]
[White "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E24"]
[Opening "Nimzo-Indian Defense: Sämisch Variation"]
[StudyName "Tal - Botvinnik, 1960"]
[ChapterName "Game 16: Botvinnik - Tal, Saemisch Nimzo Indian"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/G1YsMxfX/9KQRGfEk"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/NoseKnowsAll"]

{ Knowing full well that this 5... Ne4 idea against the Saemisch Nimzo-Indian would no longer come as a surprise to Botvinnik, Tal decided to stick to his guns and "enter the lion's dead" by repeating it anyway. }
1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nc3 { Botvinnik repeats the Nimzo-Indian } 3... Bb4 4. a3 Bxc3+ 5. bxc3 Ne4!? { Tal repeats Ne4 from game 14. } 6. Qc2!? { "A move which is recommended by all the theoretical text books. Nevertheless, after this move, in my opinion, black experiences no difficulties." Indeed, Tal is spot on. Even to this day, this is not the best option. Botvinnik played it in exactly 3 minutes, so indeed he has done his homework. } (6. e3! { The best option according to the database and SF 16. This idea will be played in game 20. }) 6... f5 7. Nh3 { A fine move, but Botvinnik took more than 15 minutes to play it. } 7... d6?! (7... O-O!? { Played in game 18. Objectively, this is probably a better option. }) 8. f3 Nf6 9. e4 (9. Bg5?! e5! 10. e3 h6 11. Bh4 Qe7 $10 { Tolush - Lutikov, 1958. This perfectly resembles a dutch. }) 9... fxe4 10. fxe4 (10. Ng5!? { Amazingly the engine seems to like this odd move if white wants an advantage. Insane. } 10... exf3?! (10... O-O!? 11. Nxe4 h6 $14) 11. Bd3 Qe7 12. O-O! fxg2 13. Qxg2! $16 { Of course, neither Botvinnik nor Tal would have ever considered such a reckless abandonment of the center. Visually, this position is quite appealing for white though - the best way to punish someone not following the principles is to blast open the center ASAP and use this bishop pair to its maximum. }) 10... e5! { Limiting white in the center, similar to a Hubner Nimzo-Indian idea, a la Spassky - Fischer, 1972. } (10... O-O? 11. e5! dxe5 12. dxe5 Ng4 13. Bg5 $16 { Tal's line is good for white. }) 11. Nf2!? { The knight has to spin into the game one way or another. } (11. Ng5!? { A more active version - rerouting to f3 instead. }) 11... O-O 12. Be2 { Taimanov's manuscript on the Nimzo correctly claimed this position was equal. } 12... c5!? { Tal is looking to shut down the bishop pair for good. } 13. dxe5!? (13. d5! { "Of course, locking the center with d5 would have been a gross mistake, since a position that was rather closed would arise in which the bishops are extraordinarily difficult to activate." Hilariously, the engine loves this move - claiming that black's queenside pieces are too far away from the kingside. This hearkens back to an earlier Tal quote. "In reality, specifically good moves are usually preferable to continuations that are considered good only on general principles." If we take this a bit further... } 13... Nbd7!? (13... Qe7!? 14. Be3 Nbd7 15. g4! $14) (13... Qe8!? 14. g4! Qf7 15. Be3 $14) 14. g4! Qe8 15. h4! h5 16. g5 Nh7 $14 { it becomes clear that black is not happy with the current situation on the kingside. If only we could put our king on c7 here... }) (13. Be3?! { Maintaining the tension is logical, but now black can successfully play } 13... cxd4 14. cxd4 Nc6 15. d5 Nd4!? (15... Qa5+! 16. Qd2 Qxd2+ 17. Kxd2 Na5 $10 { [%cal Ga5b3,Ga5c4] }) 16. Bxd4 exd4 $14 { with nice outposts on e5 and c5. }) 13... dxe5 14. O-O { Black is denied the d4 outpost, but the position remains a bit too fixed for the player possessing the bishop pair to be so happy about this position. } 14... Nc6 15. Bg5!? (15. Nd1! { Transferring the knight to d5 immediately. "The struggle becomes more complicated and, in my opinion, Botvinnik should have played it. } 15... Bg4!? (15... Nd4?? { The fact that Tal even considered such a brash move really speaks to his dynamic nature. } 16. cxd4 Qxd4+ 17. Ne3 Qxa1 18. Bb2! Qa2 19. Ra1 $18) 16. Bxg4 Nxg4 17. Rxf8+ Qxf8 18. h3 Nf6 19. Ne3 Nh5! $10 { The g3 and f4 holes are just as relevant as d5. }) 15... Qe8 16. Nd1! (16. Nd3!? { Hits the c5 pawn. Tal was delusional here and started to panic as he calculated the variation: } 16... Nxe4 17. Rxf8+ Qxf8 18. Nxe5 { Obviously in retrospect this is a simple blunder. } 18... Nxg5 19. Qxh7+! { Mate! It was only after a minute or so that he realized the knight on g5 was a black knight, not a white knight, and he realized this entire calculation was completely nonsense! }) 16... Qg6 { Forces exchanges. } 17. Bxf6 (17. Be3? Bh3 $17) 17... Rxf6 18. Ne3 { Botvinnik completes his nice regrouping. } (18. Rxf6?! Qxf6 19. Ne3 Qg5 20. Nd5 Bh3 $15) 18... Rxf1+ (18... Be6!? 19. Nf5! $10) 19. Rxf1 Be6 { The exchanges of more pieces mean that Nf5 and a huge kingside attack are less likely to be fatal. } (19... Qg5!? 20. Rf3! $10 { [%cal Gf3g3] }) 20. Qd3 Rd8 (20... Rf8?! 21. Qd6 Rxf1+ 22. Bxf1 $10 { White's queen is annoying. }) 21. Nd5 Rf8 { This casual offer a rook trade was made in less than 1 minutes. } (21... Rd7! $10 { Tal (correctly) thinks this move achieves full equality. The knight is dominated for now, and Rf7 is coming with soothing trades. }) 22. Nc7! { "By itself, the knight poses no danger to black. But after the exchange of rooks, the queen will come to its aid and then this tandem will attack on the queenside." } 22... Rxf1+ { Played after a 20 minute think during which Tal ensured himself that the queenside threats don't amount to anything. } (22... Rd8!? { Tal thinks that repeating with the rook is a good try, even though it allows white to try to win with } 23. Nxe6!? (23. Nd5!? Rd7! $10) 23... Qxe6 24. Qf3 { After which white is fully in control of the f file. Of course, the engine says that means nothing with such a horrible bishop on e2 and claims that after } 24... Qe7 25. h4 Rd6! $15 { Black is in fact the one pushing here with Nd8->e6->f4 and Rf6 or Rg6 coming. }) 23. Bxf1 Qf7 { Solid. } (23... Bf7?! 24. Qd7 $14) (23... Bc8?! 24. Qd5+ Qf7 25. Nb5! $14) 24. Qd6 Bc8! { Solid defense. The knight is no longer actively employed on c7. } (24... Bxc4?? 25. Bxc4 Qxc4 26. Ne6! Kf7 27. Qf8+ Kxe6 28. Qg8+ $18) 25. Na6! { A very nice winning attempt played after 25 minutes. Botvinnik has used 2 hours to reach this position, against Tal's 1 hour 10 minutes. } (25. Nd5!? { The most active move. } 25... Qf8 26. Qc7 { White seems more active, but Tal found two ways to force a draw: } 26... Qe8! $10 { Qd7 is coming to force the queen trade. } { [%cal Ge8d7] } (26... Kh8! $10 { Qd8 is coming to force a queen trade. }) (26... Qd8?? 27. Qxd8+ Nxd8 28. Ne7+ $18 { The reason that Kh8 first is necessary. })) (25. Qd5!? Qxd5 26. cxd5 Na5 { A very complicated endgame arises. } 27. d6? (27. Bb5!? $10) 27... c4! $17) (25. Nb5!? Qe7! (25... a6?! 26. Nc7! { Nxa6 is coming with some serious threats. }) 26. Qxe7 Nxe7 27. Nxa7 Bd7! $10 { "The extra pawn does not mean anything." }) 25... Qf4! { Completely abandoning the queenside, Tal seeks counterplay against white's king now. e4 is attacked first and foremost. } (25... Qe7!? 26. Qxe7 Nxe7 27. Nxc5 $10 { "Perhaps sufficient to secure a draw, but in any case, it is not easy." }) 26. Qd5+ (26. Nxc5?? Qe3+ 27. Kh1 Qf2 $19) (26. Qxc5?! Qxe4 $10) 26... Kh8 27. Qxc5 Be6! { Finishing development again, preventing the mate, once again attacking e4, and potentially preparing Nd4! } (27... Qxe4?? 28. Qf8# { The point of first checking on d5. }) 28. Nc7!? (28. a4?? { Or any other passing move to show Tal's point. } 28... Nd4? { Tal wanted to recklessly abandon everything and go for white's king. Yet there is a tricky win here for white. } (28... bxa6! 29. Qxc6 Qe3+ 30. Kh1 Qf2 $19 { A much cleaner version of what Tal was trying to show. }) 29. cxd4 Qe3+ 30. Kh1 Qf2! { Tal's idea fails to: } 31. d5! Qxf1+ 32. Qg1! { And white cannot trade into the king and pawn endgame. } 32... Qxg1+ 33. Kxg1 bxa6 34. dxe6 Kg8 35. c5 Kf8 36. c6 Ke7 37. c7 $18) (28. Nb4!? { Tal's recommendation. } 28... b6! 29. Qf2 Qxf2+ (29... Qxe4?? 30. Bd3 $18) 30. Kxf2 Nb8! $10) 28... Bg8 { Black defends the bishop and protects against Qf8+. What is white's point? } 29. Qf2 { A sad defensive move played after 15 minutes. Botvinnik only has 11 minutes left to reach time control... AGAIN. } 29... Qxe4 30. Ne8 Qg6 { Kicks the knight out unless white wants to commit to an "attack." } 31. Qf8 e4! { Preventing Bd3 with a deflection from g7. The position remains sharp and Botvinnik has little time remaining. Ne5->f3 might be an idea. } 32. Nd6 Ne5 33. c5! { Bc4 coming next. White is successfully using the extra pawn to activate his pieces. But Botvinnik only has 6 minutes left... } 33... Nd3?! { "A serious blunder." It's fine but now he might be on the worse side of equal. } (33... Qg5! { Tal's suggestion after the fact. } 34. Nf5? (34. Bc4? Qc1+! 35. Kf2 Qd2+ 36. Kf1 (36. Kg3?? Qe3+ 37. Kh4 Ng6+ $19) 36... Qd1+ 37. Kf2 e3+! 38. Kxe3 Nxc4+ 39. Nxc4 Qb3 $17) (34. h3!? { A good way to prevent the queen from wreaking havoc against white's king. } 34... h6 35. Nxe4?! (35. Kh2! $10 { White remains on the better side of equal here, with his king safe and Nxe4 actually a threat. }) 35... Qe3+ 36. Nf2 Qxc3 $15 { Tal thought that black deserved more than this position and messed up badly. }) 34... Nd7! 35. h4 Qg6 36. Qxg8+ Kxg8 37. Ne7+ Kf7 38. Nxg6 Kxg6 $19 { The pawns are all dropping on the queenside. }) 34. Nf5 Ne5?! { Tal admits his mistake but now is down two tempi in a sharp position. } (34... Qg5?! 35. h4 Qf4?? (35... Qf6! 36. Qxf6 gxf6 37. Bxd3 exd3 $14 { White is the one pushing here for sure. }) 36. Qxg7#) (34... Qf7!? { It's sad to have to trade into this endgame, but } 35. Qxf7 Bxf7 36. Bxd3 exd3 37. Kf2 g6 38. Nd6 Bd5 $10 { Black is not worse here. }) 35. Ne7! Qf7! { At least white keeps the knight on the board here, but this is a further tempo loss compared to the earlier Qf7. } 36. Qxf7 (36. Qxg8+? Qxg8 37. Nxg8 Kxg8 38. Kf2 Nd7! 39. c6 bxc6 40. Ke3 Nf6 41. Kd4 Kf7 $10 { White's compensation for being down a pawn is his active king. }) 36... Bxf7 37. Kf2 { The pawn on c5 is strong and Ke3->e4 is coming. } 37... Bc4?! { Tal gives this an exclam, but there is a fly in the ointment. } (37... Ng4+! { The engine finds some nonsense here to not be worse. } 38. Kg3!? (38. Kg1!? Ne5 $10 { No progress yet. }) (38. Ke1!? g5 $14 { But the white king isn't a contributing factor yet. }) 38... Ne3! 39. Be2 g5! $10 { And the king is boxed out from coming up the board. }) 38. Bxc4! (38. c6?! bxc6 (38... Nxc6? 39. Ng6+! hxg6 40. Bxc4 $16) 39. Nxc6! { And white has a good endgame... except for one thing: } 39... e3+!! 40. Kxe3!? (40. Kg1!? Bxf1 41. Nxe5 Be2 $10 { The bishop is not worse than the knight, and white's king is doing nothing. }) 40... Bxf1 41. Nxe5 Bxg2 42. Kd4 g6 43. Kc5 Kg7 44. Kd6 Kf6 $10 { Black's kingside majority is fast if white over-commits on the queenside. }) 38... Nxc4 39. c6? { Botvinnik misses a win with only 2 minutes on his clock. However, neither Tal nor any of the commentators seemed to have considered 40. Ke3 as a missed winning resource, so nobody lost any sleep over the time scramble. } (39. Nc8! Nxa3 40. Ke3! $18 { But white can run their king up the board ASAP and not bother taking the useless a pawn. Get your king up in the endgame! } (40. Nxa7? Nc4! $10 { "The draw is obvious." })) 39... bxc6 40. Nxc6 a5 { Both sides reach time control and Botvinnik spent 15 minutes to seal his next move. } 41. a4 $10 { 1/2-1/2 The game is a draw. } { Rather than play out a trivially drawn endgame, Tal offered a draw to Botvinnik overnight from what he saw as the stronger position. Botvinnik accepted the draw in the morning before resumption. } 41... Kg8!? (41... g5!? 42. Nxa5! Nxa5 43. Ke3 Nb3 44. Kxe4 Nc5+ 45. Kf5 Nxa4 46. c4 $10 { The pawns are all dropping, and the knight by itself cannot win. }) 42. Kg3 g5 43. Kg4 h6 44. Kf5 $10 { White's king is too active, and Nd4 will stop the e pawn. } 1/2-1/2


