{ Tal came to the board trying to follow the advice of his trainer: don't go crazy and keep your tactical inclinations in check. }
1. e4 c6 { Tal thinks this is a draw offer from Botvinnik, essentially thinking it's impossible to win with the Caro-Kann unless white over-presses. } 2. d4 d5 3. Nc3 dxe4 4. Nxe4 Bf5 5. Ng3 Bg6 6. Bc4!? { Repeating the same line as earlier in the match, but now Botvinnik plays most precisely. } (6. h4!? h6 7. Nf3 Nd7 8. Bd3!? $10 { Tal felt that sticking with the main line would give him the best chances for a draw if equality is all he's looking for, but for some reason he repeats his Bc4 ideas. } (8. h5!? Bh7 9. Bd3 Bxd3 10. Qxd3 e6 11. Bf4 Qa5+ 12. Bd2 Qc7 $10 { Indeed this modern mainline position is roughly level. })) (6. f4?! { As a side note, Tal mentions this anti-positional move as a way to go for an immediate attack. } 6... e6 7. h4! h6 8. Nf3 Nd7 9. Ne5 $10 { This was too double-edged to try, given the match situation. }) 6... e6 7. N1e2 Nf6! 8. Nf4!? (8. O-O!? Bd6 9. f4 Qc7!? (9... Bf5! $10 { Makagonov's recommendation to kill white's fun. }) 10. f5 exf5 11. Nxf5 Bxh2+?! (11... Bxf5! 12. Rxf5 Nbd7 $10 { The proper way to end white's fu. }) 12. Kh1 $14 { Paul Keres had a few games in this position. }) (8. h4!? h6 9. Nf4 Bh7 { Repeating their old move orders. }) 8... Bd6! { The most precise move order from black. Now h4 goes nowhere. } 9. Nxg6!? { Tal opts for taking the LSB while he can. Black's open h file doesn't amount to much. } (9. h4?! { Doesn't get white anywhere with black's precise move order. } 9... Qc7 10. h5 Bxc2! 11. Nxe6! Bxd1!? (11... fxe6!? 12. Qxc2 Bxg3 13. fxg3 Qxg3+ 14. Qf2 Qxf2+ 15. Kxf2 $15) 12. Nxc7+ Bxc7 13. Kxd1 $10) (9. O-O!? Nbd7 10. Re1 $10 { Black can try for e5, but white's pieces remain reasonably well-placed. }) 9... hxg6 10. Bg5?! { Inconsistent. This might run into a timely Ne4 once black gets out of the pin. } (10. O-O $10 { The most consistent. }) 10... Nbd7 11. O-O (11. Qe2!? { with the idea of going queenside spices up the position. But this is also fraught with the type of double-edged danger that Tal was responsibly trying to avoid. }) (11. c3!? Qa5 12. h4 $10 { Apparently this is equal, but this is not obvious to a human. }) 11... Qa5! { Black is at least fine here. } 12. f4?! { Every commentator admonished Tal for such an anti-positional decision, and indeed it is not a great move. Tal notes that yes this move weakens the dark squares, locks the bishop on g5 out of the game, and weakens white's king. However, during the eight minute think here, Tal decided he didn't have any opening advantage at all. And since every option was mediocre at best, he decided that forcing Botvinnik to try and refute his suboptimal move would require sharpening up the position. } (12. Qd2!? Qxd2 13. Bxd2 $10 { "It would not have been unlikely that a draw would have resulted." }) 12... O-O-O! { Botvinnik takes up the challenge after 10 minutes. He will indeed try and refute Tal's play - doubly-so because he is trailing in the match. } (12... O-O?! $15 { Obviously this move is playable too, but this is not a refutation of f4. }) 13. a3 { Going call-in on the queenside isn't that smart in general when the center can explode. Yet here, it's tough to get in a freeing break. e5 is obviously out of the question, so c5 becomes the main candidate. } 13... Qc7! { Avoiding b4 with tempo, and preparing Nb6->d5. But Botvinnik spent 30 minutes on just this one move. } (13... c5?! 14. b4! cxb4?! (14... Qc7! 15. bxc5 Bxc5! $15 { and the bishop on c4 is loose. Still, this isn't that convincing of a sequence for black. }) 15. axb4 Qxb4 16. Be2 $10 { with Bf3 coming. White has ample compensation on the open lines and diagonals towards black's king. } { [%cal Ge2f3] }) 14. b4?! (14. Qe1!? { Potentially the most useful move in the position. c5 is still playable, but now you're opening up lines to the king on c8. } 14... c5! (14... Rde8!? 15. h3! Nh7? 16. Ne4! Bf8!? (16... Nxg5!? 17. fxg5 $14 { White's pieces are beautifully centralized. }) 17. Bh4 $10 { The bishop reroutes to f2 and white remains totally fine here. Black has made odd moves trying to punish white here instead of positionally sound moves. }) 15. c3! cxd4 16. cxd4 Kb8 (16... Qxc4?? 17. Rc1 $16) 17. Rc1 $17 { This might be the best that black can do. But this is not a huge accomplishment for black. }) 14... Nb6?! { Clear, strategic play from Botvinnik. But he is missing the precise moves necessary to refute Tal - exactly as Tal was hoping would be the case. } (14... Rde8! { Preparing Nh7 and f6 to kill the bishop. } 15. Qe1?! Nh7! 16. Ne4? Nxg5! 17. fxg5?? { With h3 inserted, white would be totally fine here. Without h3 inserted... } 17... Bxh2+! $19) 15. Be2 Be7?! { Another logical, slow move - preparing Nfd5. But this is not the type of move that tries to refute white's play. } (15... Nfd5! 16. Bxd8 Qxd8 $17 { With dark square weaknesses everywhere, a weak kingside, and inactive rooks, black is totally in control here too. }) (15... e5! { Another spicy move that commentators noted after the fact. } 16. fxe5!? Bxe5 17. Bg4+ Kb8 18. c3 { "White's bishop are extremely active," but yes objectively black is doing great here with white's king on the chopping block. That can be underscored with the following sequence: } 18... Rxh2!! 19. Kxh2 Bxg3+ 20. Kg1 Rh8! { Black's king is looking highly suspicious and if the b6 knight can spring into the attack, the game would be over instantly. } 21. Qf3!? Nfd5! 22. Bh3!? (22. Qxf7?? Bh2+ 23. Kh1 Bf4+ 24. Kg1 Qxf7 $19) 22... f6 23. Bc1 g5 $17) 16. Qd3 Nfd5? { Objectively and psychologically poor. Objectively poor because now white can play for c4 with tempo. Psychologically poor because the entire idea of "trapping" white's misplaced g5 bishop is gone forever. } (16... c5! { Tal notes this spicy move. } 17. c3!? (17. bxc5? { Tal was willing to go in for these complications. } 17... Rxd4! 18. cxb6 (18. Qxd4?? Bxc5 $19) 18... Rxd3 19. bxc7 Bc5+ 20. Kh1 (20. Rf2?? Rxg3! 21. hxg3 Ne4! 22. Rf1 Nxg3 $19 { Rh1# is unstoppable. }) 20... Rxg3 21. Bxf6! (21. Bf3? Ng4! 22. h3?! (22. Bxg4!? Rxg4 $19) 22... Ne3 23. Rfc1 Rxf3! $19) 21... gxf6 22. Bf3 $17 { "I do not think that white has to lose."
This very well may be Tal's best analytical work in the entire book. Every variation he considered was objectively correct and evaluated properly except for 17. c3 c4 being positionally losing for white. Fantastic variations. }) 17... c4!? $10 { Tal rejects c3 since white gets all the fun now that black's king is safe. But in reality, white's center is finally stable and so there's no catastrophe waiting to happen here. }) (16... Kb8!? 17. c3! { might be the safest way for white to continue. } 17... Rd7!? $10 (17... c5?! 18. bxc5 Bxc5 (18... Rxd4?? { The entire conception of the other line now fails since white does not need to recapture on d4 with the queen. } 19. cxd4! $18) 19. Rab1 $10)) 17. Bxe7 Qxe7 (17... Nxe7!? 18. Ne4 $14) 18. c4! Nf6?! { Tal now felt that his earlier f4 move had been completely justified. } (18... Nxc4!? 19. Qxc4 Qh4? { a big decision for black. Does this win or fall flat. } (19... Ne3! 20. Qc3 Nxf1 21. Nxf1 { It's hard to imagine this being playable. But after: } 21... Qd6! { white can simply not defend both the d and f pawns. } 22. Rd1 Qxf4 23. g3 $10) 20. Rf3! { Tal spotted the correct defense. } 20... Nxf4 21. h3! Rxd4 22. Qc5! $18 { The bishop is significantly stronger than the extra pawns. }) 19. Rab1!? { Over-protecting b4 prepares a4+a5. } (19. a4?! { It is tempting to storm the queenside in such a manner. } 19... Qxb4 20. a5 Nxc4! { Tal rejected this line because of this piece sacrifice which defuses the queenside attack. } 21. Qxc4!? (21. Rfb1? { Tal actually thought this move was stronger for white than taking the free piece. But he missed an important resource. } 21... Qd2! 22. Qxc4?? Qe3+! { A line missed by Tal. } (22... Qxd4+?? 23. Qxd4 Rxd4 { Tal thought this line was enough for black. }) 23. Kf1!? (23. Kh1!? Rxh2+! 24. Kxh2 Rh8+ $19) 23... Ne4!! 24. Nxe4 Rxh2! $19 { There is no adequate defense to Rdh8 and Rh1#. }) 21... Qxc4 22. Bxc4 Rxd4 $10) (19. h3! $14 { Simply ruling out the h file shenanigans now is objectively best. This is not a hook that black can latch onto because of white's earlier f4. }) 19... Qd7! { But black correctly pressures white's center before the queenside attack gets off the ground. } 20. Rbd1!? { Played after 20 minutes. White still maintains a 20 minute lead on the clock, and he is in no way lost due to his opening choice. But the position is still tense, and his last few moves have not inspired confidence. } (20. Rfd1!? Rh4 21. Qe3?! (21. Bf3! Rxf4 22. Ne2! Rh4 23. g3 Rh3 24. b5 $16 { An extremely spice engine line that shows how to refute greedy play. The queenside will open after: } 24... c5 25. a4! cxd4 26. a5! $16) 21... Qd6! $10) 20... Kb8 { Defending a7 means that a4 now comes as a true pawn sacrifice. } 21. Qb3 { Prepares a4 and gets the queen off the d file. } (21. a4?! Nxa4 22. Qa3 Nb6 23. Rd2 { [%cal Gf1a1] } 23... Nc8! $17 { The pressure on a7 is no more and black is up a clean pawn. }) 21... Qc7! 22. a4 Rh4 23. a5 (23. Qe3?! Nxa4 $15) 23... Nc8 24. Qe3 { Black has strengthened his queenside, but white has gained space and is finally well-coordinated... assuming the pressure on the h file doesn't ruin his day.
Both players have 40 minutes remaining for 16 moves. } 24... Ne7 25. Qe5! Rhh8?! (25... Qxe5? 26. fxe5 $16 { Way too strong of a cramp. }) (25... Rdh8?! 26. h3 Nf5 27. Nxf5 gxf5 $14 { Black gains the e4 square for the knight, but the attack is done forever. Either white gets a cramping pawn on e5 or keeps the space advantage with pieces on the board. }) (25... a6!? $10 { It might be necessary to prevent white's undermining a6 move and just plan for an equal endgame. }) 26. b5?! { Not horrendous, but as Tal notes this gives up the d5 square forever or doesn't open lines to black's king after all. } (26. a6! { The correct way forward. } 26... b6 (26... bxa6?! 27. Ra1 $16) 27. Bf3 $14 { The a pawn is a true thorn in black's position. White hasn't opened up lines to black's king, but the pieces are playing and white's center is not a weakness. }) 26... cxb5 27. Qxb5 { "The weakness of white's pawns take on a catastrophic character." } (27. cxb5?! Rd5 $17) (27. Rc1! { The engine comes up with some crazy line to equalize here as white. } 27... b4 28. Bf3! Kc8 29. a6! bxa6 30. Rb1! Qd6 31. Rfd1 $10 { Nope. This line is inhuman for sure. }) 27... a6!? (27... Nc6! 28. Qb2 { Tal's idea is correct. But indeed this is a pawn sacrifice: } 28... Nxa5 $15) 28. Qb2 { White's pawns are weak, but at least black is not up a pawn. The open b file to black's king may matter. } 28... Rd7! { Defends b7 and prepares to double. } 29. c5! { a la Capablanca's idea. If white can land a knight on d6, black is dead. The argument that the d5 square doesn't matter as much as the d6 square is a contentious one, but possibly correct. } 29... Ka8 30. Bf3 Nc6 { Both knights are in a standstill. Black does not want to play Nd5 without allowing Ne4->d6. White does not want to trade knights, nor play Ne2, which is a bit passive. Tal comes up with another creative idea. } (30... Rhd8?! 31. c6? { Tal's idea to sacrifice a pawn isn't good. } 31... Nxc6 $17 { The open c file doesn't give white's pieces any more activity. }) (30... Nfd5!? 31. Ne4!? Ne3 32. Nd6 $10 { Even at the cost of an exchange, white's knight is a monster on d6. }) (30... Ned5?! { Golombek (the head arbiter of this match) recommended this move. } 31. Rd3! Nxf4 32. Rb3 $16 { The b pawn can't be guarded well: } 32... N6d5!? 33. Ne4! $16 { Nd6 is coming again to hit b7. } { [%cal Ge4d6] }) 31. Bxc6!? { Highly contentious. Now d4 will be a rock, and white is going to try and get his tricky knight into the attack. } (31. Rd3! { Would have probably been safer. Tal was too worried about the threat to d4. } 31... Nxd4? (31... Rhd8!? 32. Ne2! Nd5 33. Rb1 $14) 32. Rxd4 Qxc5 33. Ne2 $18) 31... Qxc6 32. Rf3 { Heading for b6. } 32... Qa4 33. Rfd3!? { Tal gives this an exclam because it takes the sting out of Rhd8. } (33. Rb3!? Rhd8 34. Ne2 Nd5 $10) 33... Rc8 (33... Rhd8!? 34. Ne2 Nd5 35. Rb1 $10 { The queen doesn't eye d3. Hence why Rd3 and not Rb3 is more accurate. }) 34. Rb1 { The correct rook hits the b file. } 34... Qxa5?! { Winning material, but doing so with only 9 minutes to reach the time control. Moreover, white's knight has a beautiful re-route now: } 35. Rb3!? { Tal finds another practically strong move. Black only has one move in response. } (35. Nf1! Qc7 36. Ne3! $16 { Nc4->b6+ is deadly. }) 35... Qc7?! (35... Qa4! 36. Rxb7 Qxd4+! 37. Qxd4 Rxd4 38. Rxf7 Rxc5 $10) 36. Qa3!? { 5 minutes remaining for Tal. 3 minutes remaining for Botvinnik. } (36. Nf1! $16 { The same maneuver to b6 is deadly. }) 36... Ka7 37. Rb6 { Tal goes all-in. c6 is his threat. } 37... Qxf4 38. Ne2! { Defending d4 prepares c6 again. } (38. c6?? Qxd4+! 39. Kf1 Qc4+ $19) (38. Qb4!? Qxd4+ 39. Qxd4 Rxd4 40. Rxb7+ Ka8 41. c6 $10 { Probably equal. }) 38... Qe4! { c6 is prevented, so Tal sets up another cheapo. } 39. Qb3! Qd5?? { With 1 minute on his clock, Botvinnik misses Tal's last threat. Instead, he sets up an intermediate "Woodpecker Method" problem. } (39... Ka8! { The only defensive move. "I do not maintain that then white would have a strong enough attack to save himself, but in my opinion, there would be many tactical resources in the position. Possible would be h3." } 40. h3! $10 { Correct. With Kh1 coming, there are no threats here to deal with just yet. } (40. Rxa6+?? bxa6 41. Qb6 Qxe2 $19 { A defensive option available to black now that Qb6 did not land with a check. })) 40. Rxa6+! { Played with 1 minute remaining. } 40... Kb8!? { The last try. Botvinnik has reached the time control. } (40... bxa6?! 41. Qb6+ Ka8 42. Qxa6+ Ra7 43. Qxc8# { The point. }) (40... Kxa6?! 41. Qa4#) 41. Qa4! $18 { 1-0 White wins. } { One of many winning moves. Tal played it instantly. Rather than seal a move and adjourn this obviously lost position, Botvinnik resigned right there and then. } 1-0


[Event "Botvinnik - Tal World Championship Match"]
[Site "Moscow URS"]
[Date "1960.04.28"]
[Round "18"]
[White "Mikhail Botvinnik"]
[Black "Mikhail Tal"]
[Result "1/2-1/2"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "E24"]
[Opening "Nimzo-Indian Defense: Sämisch Variation"]
